('200204003004','(i) Assume that the lines intersect;$$\\Rightarrow ( 5i + 2j + 4k ) + \\lambda ( i + 3j + k ) = ( 3i + j + k ) + \\mu ( 4i + 7j + 5k )$$ for some $$\\lambda ,\\mu \\in \\mathbb{R}$$;$$\\Rightarrow 5 + \\lambda = 3 + 4\\mu$$  -----(1);$$ 2 + 3\\lambda = 1 + 7\\mu$$                   -----(2);$$ 4 + \\lambda = 1 + 5\\mu$$                     -----(3);;Eqn (1) - (3): $$1 = 2 - \\mu$$   $$\\Rightarrow \\mu = 1$$;Eqn (1): $$ 5 + \\lambda = 3 + 4(1)$$   $$\\Rightarrow \\lambda = 2$$;Subst into Eqn(2):;$$LHS = 2 + 3(2) = 8$$;$$RHS = 1 + 7(1) = 8 =  LHS$$;$$\\therefore $$ the lines meet at $$\\mu = 1 (\\lambda = 2)$$,;i.e at $$( 3i + j + k ) + (1)( 4i + 7j + 5k )$$;$$ = 7i + 8j + 6k$$ (ans);;(ii) Let $$\\theta = $$ acute angle between the lines;$$\\Rightarrow \\theta = \\cos ^{-1}\\frac{|( i + 3j + k ).|( 4i + 7j + 5k )|}{| i + 3j + k || 4i + 7j + 5k |}$$;$$ = \\cos ^{-1}\\frac{| 4 + 21 + 5|}{\\sqrt{1^2 + 3^2 + 1^2}\\sqrt{4^2 + 7^2 + 5^2}}$$;$$ = \\cos ^{-1}(0.9535)$$;$$ = 17.56 = 17.6^{0}$$ (1 dp) (ans)'),
('200204003005','(i)$$f( x ) = x + \\frac{1}{x}, x \\ge 1$$;$$f^{\'}( x ) = \\frac{d}{dx}[x + \\frac{1}{x}] = 1 - \\frac{1}{x^2}$$;For all $$x \\ge 1$$, $$1 - \\frac{1}{x^2} \\le 1$$;$$\\Rightarrow f^{\'}( x ) = 1 - \\frac{1}{x^2} \\ge 0$$;$$\\Rightarrow f(x)$$ increases as $$x$$ increases. (ans);;(ii) Let $$y = f(x)$$, $$x \\ge 1$$;Range of $$f$$ is $$y \\ge 2$$ (ans);;(iii) Let $$y = f^{- 1}( x )$$;$$\\Rightarrow f(y) = x$$;$$  y + \\frac{1}{y} = x$$;$$ y^2 + 1  = xy$$;$$ y^2 - xy = -1 $$;$$ y^2 - xy + \\frac{1}{4}x^2 = \\frac{1}{4}x^2 - 1$$;$$ (y - \\frac{1}{2}x)^2  =  \\frac{1}{4}x^2 - 1$$;$$ y - \\frac{1}{2}x = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{4}x^2 - 1}$$;$$ y = \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{4}x^2 - 1} + \\frac{1}{2}x$$;$$\\therefore f^{- 1}: x \\mapsto \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{4}x^2 - 1} + \\frac{1}{2}x$$, $$x \\ge 2$$ (ans)'),
('200204003023','Let $$X$$ = mass of an apple;Let $$\\mu=E(X)$$;Let $$\\sigma^2 = Var(X)$$;P( X > 125) = 0.1;;$$\\Rightarrow P ( Z > \\frac{125 - \\mu}{\\sigma} ) = 0.1$$ ;$$ 1 - \\Phi(\\frac{125 - \\mu}{\\sigma}) = 0.1 \\equiv \\Phi(\\frac{125 - \\mu}{\\sigma}) = 0.9$$ ;$$ \\frac{125 - \\mu}{\\sigma} = \\Phi^{- 1} ( 0.9 ) = 1.282$$ ;$$ \\mu + 1.282 \\sigma = 125$$ ;$$ P ( X < 75 ) = 0.13$$ ;$$ P(Z < \\frac{75 - \\mu}{\\sigma}) = 0.13 $$ ;$$ \\Phi ( \\frac{75 - \\mu}{\\sigma} ) = 0.13 $$;$$ \\frac{75 - \\mu}{\\sigma}= \\Phi^{- 1}(0.13) = - \\Phi^{- 1}(0.87) $$ ;$$ = - \\Phi^{- 1} ( 0.8686 + 0.0014 ) = - 1.127$$;$$\\mu - 1.127$$, $$\\sigma = 75$$ ;$$ 1.127\\mu + 1.282\\mu = 1.127 \\times 125 + 1.282 \\times 75$$ ;$$ 2.409 \\mu = 237.025$$ ;$$ \\mu = 98.391 = 98.4$$ g'),
('200204003024','(i) Let $$n$$ = sample size = 120;Let $$\\mu$$ = mean speed;Let $$\\sigma^2$$ = variance of speed;$$\\hat{\\mu} = \\overline{x} = \\frac{\\sum ( x - c )}{n} + c = \\frac{- 221}{120} + 100$$ ;$$ = 98.158 = 98.16 kmh^{-1}$$;$$\\hat{\\sigma}^2 = \\frac{1}{n - 1} [ \\sum ( x - c )^2 - \\frac{1}{n} ( \\sum ( x - c )^2 ]$$ ;$$ = \\frac{1}{119}[(4708) - \\frac{1}{120}(- 221)^2]$$  ;$$ = 36.143 = 36.14 (kmh^{-1})^2$$ (ans);;(ii) $${z}_{0.02} \\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{\\sigma}^2}{n}} = 2.054\\sqrt{\\frac{36.143}{120}} = 1.127$$ ;The symmetric 96% confidence interval for $$\\mu$$;$$ = [ \\hat{\\mu} - {z}_{0.02} \\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{\\sigma}^2}{n}} , \\hat{\\mu} + {z}_{0.02} \\sqrt{\\frac{\\hat{\\sigma}^2}{n}} ]$$ ;$$ = [ 98.158 - 1.127, 98.158 + 1.127 ]$$ ;$$ = [ 97.031 , 99.285 ]$$ ;$$ = [ 97.03, 99.29 ]$$ (ans)'),
('200204003025','No. of ways to take 3 of 6 balls = $${}^{6}{C}_{3}$$;No. of ways to take 2 of 2 green balls = $${}^{2}{C}_{2}$$;No. of ways to take 1 of 4 red balls = $${}^{4}{C}_{1}$$;;$$P ( G = 2 ) = \\frac{{}^{2}{C}_{2} \\times {}^{4}{C}_{1}}{{}^{6}{C}_{3}} = \\frac{1}{5}$$ (ans);;No of ways to take 3 of 4 red calls = $${}^{4}{C}_{3}$$;$$P ( G = 0 ) = \\frac{{}^{4}{C}_{3}}{{}^{6}{C}_{3}} = \\frac{1}{5}$$;;No of ways to take 1 of 2 green balls = $${}^{2}{C}_{1}$$;No of ways to take 2 of 4 red balls = $${}^{4}{C}_{2}$$;$$P ( G = 1 ) = \\frac{{}^{2}{C}_{1} \\times {}^{4}{C}_{2}}{{}^{6}{C}_{3}} = \\frac{3}{5}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ Probability distribution of G is: ;img;(ans);;$$ E( G ) = \\sum \\limits_{all g} g . P( G = g ) = 0 \\cdot \\frac{1}{5} + 1 \\cdot \\frac{3}{5} + 2 \\cdot \\frac{1}{5} = 1$$ ;$$ E(G^2) = \\sum \\limits_{all g}g^2 \\cdot P(G = g)$$ ;$$ = 0^2 \\cdot \\frac{1}{5} + 1^2 \\cdot \\frac{3}{5} + 2^2 \\cdot \\frac{1}{5} = \\frac{7}{5}$$;$$Var(G) = E(G^2) - [ E(G) ]^2$$ ;$$ = \\frac{7}{5} - 1^2 = \\frac{2}{5}$$ (ans)'),
('200204003026','Let $$n$$ = sample size = 80;Let $$p$$ = proportion of Grade A eggs;Let $${p}_{0}$$ = assumed p = 60% = 0.6;      $${q}_{0} = 1- {p}_{0} = 0.4$$;Let $${p}_{s}$$ = sample p = 42/80 = 0.525;and $${q}_{s} = 1 - {p}_{s} = 0.475$$; ;Test $${H}_{0}: p = {p}_{0}$$ against $${H}_{1}: p < {p}_{0}$$ ;a 1- tailed test for less ;The 5 % critical value, $${z}_{0.05} = 1.645$$;Reject $${H}_{0}$$ if $$z < - {z}_{0.05}$$;Under $${H}_{0}$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \\frac{{p}_{s} - {p}_{0}}{\\sqrt{{p}_{0}{q}_{0} / n}} = \\frac{0.525 - 0.6}{\\sqrt{( 0.6 ) ( 0.4 ) / 80}} = - 1.369$$;Since $$z > - {z}_{0.05}$$, do not reject $${H}_{0}$$ and conclude that, at the 5% significance level, there is insufficient evidence that the farm is failing to reach the target of at least 60% of eggs should be grade A.;The expression \'at the 5% significance level\' refers to the probability that a correct null hypothesis, i.e. at least 60% of the eggs are Grade A, would be rejected by the test.'),
('200204003027','Let $$n$$ = sample size;Let $$p$$ = P(success) and $$q = 1 - p$$;;Let $$X \\sim B(n,p)$$;$$E(X) = 12 \\Rightarrow np=12$$    ---(1);$$Var(X) = 8 \\Rightarrow npq = 8$$ ---(2);Eqn (2)/(1): $$q = \\frac{2}{3}$$ ;$$\\Rightarrow p = 1 - q  = 1 - \\frac{2}{3}= \\frac{1}{3}$$;Eqn(1): $$n ( \\frac{1}{3} ) = 12 \\Rightarrow n = 36$$ ;;$$ P ( X = 12 ) = {}^{n}{C_{12}} p^{12} q^{24} = {}^{36}{C_{12}} {( \\frac{1}{3} )}^{12} {( \\frac{2}{3} )}^{24}$$ ;$$ = 0.1399 = 0.140$$ (ans);;Since $$n (= 36)$$ is quite large, $$np = 12 > 5$$ and $$nq = 24 > 5$$,;$$X \\sim N(np,npq)$$ approximately;$$P ( X > 13 )$$ ;$$ = P(X > 13.5) \\leftarrow$$ continuity correction ;$$ = P ( Z > \\frac{13.5 - np}{\\sqrt{npq}} ) = P ( Z > \\frac{13.5 - 12}{36 ( \\frac{1}{3} ) ( \\frac{2}{3} )} )$$ ;$$ = P(Z > 0.5303) = 1 - \\Phi(0.530)$$ ;$$ = 1 - 0.7019 = 0.2981 = 0.298$$ (ans)'),
('200204003028','Let $$X$$ = mass of a melon;Let $$Y$$ = mass of a pumpkin;$$X \\sim N(0.8,(0.1)^2)$$;$$Y \\sim N(1.2,(0.2)^2)$$;;Required probability is ;$$P(1.50({X}_{1} + {X}_{2} + {X}_{3} + {X}_{4} + {X}_{5}) + 0.50({Y}_{1} + {Y}_{2} + {Y}_{3}) > 8)$$;where $${X}_{1} , {X}_{2} , {X}_{3} , {X}_{4} , {X}_{5}$$ are weight of 5 randomly chosen melons, $${Y}_{1} , {Y}_{2} , {Y}_{3}$$ are weights of 3 randomly chosen pumpkins.;;Let $$C = 1.50 ( {X}_{1} + {X}_{2} + {X}_{3} + {X}_{4} + {X}_{5} ) + 0.50 ({Y}_{1} + {Y}_{2} + {Y}_{3})$$;$${\\mu}_{c} = E ( C ) = ( 1.50 ) 5E( X ) + ( 0.50 ) 3E ( Y )$$ ;$$ = (1.50)5(0.8) + (0.50)3(1.2) = 7.8$$ ;$$ {{\\sigma}_{c}}^2 = Var(C)$$ ;$$ = ( 1.50 )^2 5Var( X ) + ( 0.50 )^2 3Var( Y )$$ ;$$ =(1.50)^2 5(0.1)^2 + (0.50)^2 3(0.2)^2$$ ;$$ = 0.1425$$; ;$$ C \\sim N({\\mu}_{c}, {\\sigma_c}^2)$$ ;$$P(1.50({X}_{1} + {X}_{2} + {X}_{3} + {X}_{4} + {X}_{5}) + 0.50({Y}_{1} + {Y}_{2} + {Y}_{3}) > 8)$$;$$\\equiv P(C > 8)$$ ;$$ = P ( Z > \\frac{8 - {\\mu}_{c}}{{\\sigma}_{c}} ) = P ( Z > \\frac{8 - 7.8}{\\sqrt{0.1425}} )$$ ;$$ = P(Z > 0.5298)$$ ;$$ = 1 - \\Phi ( 0.530 ) = 1 - 0.7019$$;$$ = 0.2981 = 0.298$$'),
('200204003029','(i) $$F ( 3 ) = k ( 3 - 1 )^2$$ and $$F(3) = 1$$ ;$$ \\Rightarrow k ( 8 ) = 1 \\Rightarrow k = \\frac{1}{8}$$;;Let $${q}_{1}$$ = lower quartile;$$F ({q}_{1}) = \\frac{1}{4}$$ ;$$ \\frac{1}{8}({q}_{1} - 1)^3 = \\frac{1}{4}$$;$$ ( {q}_{1} - 1 )^3 = 2$$ ;$$\\therefore {q}_{1} = 1 + \\sqrt[3]{2}= 2.2599 = 2.26$$ (ans);;Let $${q}_{3}$$ = upper quartile;$$F ( {q}_{3} ) = \\frac{3}{4}$$ ;$$ \\frac{1}{8}({q}_{3} - 1)^3 = \\frac{3}{4}$$;$$ ( {q}_{3} - 1 )^3 = 6$$ ;$$\\therefore {q}_{3} = 1 + \\sqrt[3]{6}= 2.817 = 2.282$$;;(ii) $$f( x ) =  \\frac{d}{dx}F( x )$$ ;$$ = \\frac{d}{dx} [ \\frac{1}{8} ( x-1 )^3 ]$$ ;$$ = \\frac{3}{8} ( x-1 )^2$$;\\[ \\therefore f(x) = \\left\\{ ;  \\begin{array}{l l};     \\frac{3}{8} ( x-1 )^2 & \\quad \\text{for} 1 < x \\le 3 \\\\;    0 & \\quad \\text{otherwise};  \\end{array} \\right.\\] (ans);;(iii) $$E( X - 1 ) = \\int^\\infty_{-\\infty} ( x-1 )f(x )dx$$ ;$$ = \\int^3_1( x-1 )\\frac{3}{8} ( x-1 )^2dx$$ ;$$ =   \\int^3_1 \\frac{3}{8} ( x-1 )^3dx$$ ;$$ = {[ \\frac{3}{32} ( x-1 )^4 ]}^3_1$$;$$ = [ \\frac{3}{32}(2)^4 ] = \\frac{3}{2}$$ (ans);    ;$$E ( X ) = E ( X - 1 ) + 1$$ ;$$ = \\frac{3}{2}+ 1 = \\frac{5}{2}$$ (ans)'),
('200204003030','(a);(i) $$1^{st}$$ person can be born in any of 7 days;$$2^{nd}$$ person can be born in 6 of 7 days;$$3^{rd}$$ person can be born in 5 of 7 days;$$\\therefore P = \\frac{7}{7} \\times \\frac{6}{7} \\times \\frac{5}{7} = \\frac{{}^7{P}_{3}}{7^3} = \\frac{30}{49}$$ (ans);;(ii) $$4^{th}$$ person can be born in 4 of 7 days;$$\\therefore P = \\frac{7}{7} \\times \\frac{6}{7} \\times \\frac{5}{7} \\times \\frac{4}{7} = \\frac{{}^7{P}_{4}}{7^4} = \\frac{120}{343}$$ (ans);;(b) Let $$P$$ =  probability that $$n$$ people in the room were all born in different months;From the reasoning in (a), $$P = \\frac{{}^{12}{P}_{n}}{12^n}$$;$$n = 2$$ , $$P = \\frac{{}^{12}{P}_{2}}{12^2} = 0.9167$$;$$n = 3$$ , $$P = \\frac{{}^{12}{P}_{3}}{12^3} = 0.7639$$;$$n = 4$$ , $$P = \\frac{{}^{12}{P}_{4}}{12^4} = 0.5729$$;$$n = 5$$ , $$P = \\frac{{}^{12}{P}_{5}}{12^5} = 0.3819$$;$$\\therefore P < \\frac{1}{2}$$, the smallest value of $$ n = 5$$ (ans);;(c) Let $$P$$ =  probability that $$n$$ people in the room were all born in different days;From the reasoning in (a), $$P = \\frac{{}^{365}{P}_{n}}{365^n}$$; Let $$S$$ =  probability that at least 2 people in the room were born on the same day $$\\equiv 1 - P$$;$$n = 21$$ , $$P = 0.55631$$ (given);$$n = 22$$ , $$P = \\frac{{}^{365}{P}_{22}}{365^{22}} = 0.5243$$ , $$S = 0.4757$$;$$n = 23$$ , $$P = \\frac{{}^{365}{P}_{23}}{365^{23}} = 0.4927$$ , $$S = 0.5073$$;$$\\therefore S > \\frac{1}{2}$$, the smallest value of $$ n = 23$$ (ans)'),
('200204003031','$$X \\sim R(0 ,2)$$;Let $${\\mu}_{x} = E(X) = \\frac{1}{2}( 0 + 2 ) = 1$$ (ans);Let $${\\sigma}_{x}^{2} = Var(X)$$;$$ = \\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty}(x - {\\mu}_{x})^2.f(x)dx$$;$$ = \\int_{0}^{2}(x - 1)^2.(\\frac{1}{2})dx$$;$$ = [\\frac{1}{6}(x - 1)^3]_{0}^{2}$$;$$ = \\frac{1}{6}[(1) - ( -1 )] = \\frac{1}{3}$$ (ans);;Let $$n$$ = sample size = 80;Since n ( = 80) is large, Central Limit Theorem;$$\\Rightarrow S \\sim N(80{\\mu}_{x}, 80{\\sigma}_{x}^{2})$$ approximately;$$P ( 75 < S < 90)$$;$$ = P(\\frac{75 - 80{\\mu}_{x}}{\\sqrt{80{\\sigma}_{x}^{2}}} < Z < \\frac{90 - 80{\\mu}_{x}}{\\sqrt{80{\\sigma}_{x}^{2}}})$$;$$ = P(\\frac{75 - 80(1)}{\\sqrt{80(\\frac{1}{3})}} < Z < \\frac{90 - 80(1)}{\\sqrt{80(\\frac{1}{3})}})$$;$$ = P( - 0.9683 < Z < 1.93649)$$;$$\\equiv 2\\Phi(1.936) - [1 - \\Phi (0.968)]$$;$$ = 0.9736 - [1 - 0.8335]$$;$$ = 0.8071 = 0.807$$ (ans);;Let $$p = P(X < 1.9) = \\frac{1.9 - 0}{2 - 0} = 0.95$$;and $$q = 1 - p  = 0.05$$;Let $$Y$$ = no. of observations out of $$n$$ with $$X < 1.9$$;$$Y\' = n - Y$$;$$Y \\sim B(n,p)$$ and $$Y\' \\sim B(n,q)$$;Since $$n$$ ( = 80) is large and $$nq = 4 < 5$$;$$Y\' \\sim Po(\\lambda )$$ approximately, where $$\\lambda  = nq = 4$$;$$P(Y \\ge 77)$$;$$\\equiv P(Y\' \\le 3)$$;$$ = e^{-\\lambda}[\\frac{\\lambda^{0}}{0!} + \\frac{\\lambda^{1}}{1!} + \\frac{\\lambda^{2}}{2!} + \\frac{\\lambda^{3}}{3!}]$$;$$ = e^{-4}[\\frac{4^{0}}{0!} + \\frac{4^{1}}{1!} + \\frac{4^{2}}{2!} + \\frac{4^{3}}{3!}]$$;$$ =  0.43347 = 0.433$$ (ans)'),
