('200303003009','$${{x}^{3}}+2{{x}^{2}}-2=0\\equiv {{x}^{3}}=2-2{{x}^{2}}$$;Sketch $$y={{x}^{3}}$$ and $$y=2-2{{x}^{2}}$$;; img;;The graphs of $$y={{x}^{3}}$$ and $$y=2-2{{x}^{2}}$$ intersect at exactly one point where x is positive;$$\\Rightarrow$$ the equation $${{x}^{3}}=2-2{{x}^{2}}\\equiv {{x}^{3}}+2{{x}^{2}}-2=0$$ has exactly 1 positive root;;(i) ;$$\\begin{align};  & {{x}^{3}}+2{{x}^{2}}-2=0 \\\\ ; & \\equiv {{x}^{2}}\\left( x+2 \\right)=2\\equiv x=\\sqrt{\\frac{2}{x+2}} \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;Hence $$\\alpha $$ is a root of $$x=\\sqrt{\\frac{2}{x+2}}$$;;Let $$f\\left( x \\right)={{x}^{3}}+2{{x}^{2}}-2$$;Starting with x1=1,;$$\\begin{align};  & {{x}_{2}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{2}{{{x}_{1}}+2}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{2}{\\left( 1 \\right)+2}}=0.816=0.82\\left( 2sf \\right) \\\\ ; & {{x}_{3}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{2}{{{x}_{2}}+2}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{2}{\\left( 0.82 \\right)+2}}=0.842=0.84\\left( 2sf \\right) \\\\ ; & {{x}_{4}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{2}{x3+2}}=\\sqrt{\\frac{2}{\\left( 0.84 \\right)+2}}=0.839=0.84\\left( 2sf \\right) \\\\ ; & f\\left( 0.84+0.005 \\right)=0.031>0 \\\\ ; & f\\left( 0.84-0.005 \\right)=-0.023<0 \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;Correct to 2 significant figures, $$\\alpha =0.84$$;;(ii);$${{f}^{\'}}\\left( x \\right)=\\frac{d}{dx}\\left[ {{x}^{3}}+2{{x}^{2}}-2 \\right]=3{{x}^{2}}+4x$$;Newton-Raphson method with x1=1;$$\\begin{align};  & {{x}_{2}}={{x}_{1}} - \\frac{f\\left( {{x}_{1}} \\right)}{{{f}^{\'}}\\left( {{x}_{1}} \\right)}=0.8571=0.857\\left( 3sf \\right) \\\\ ; & {{x}_{3}}={{x}_{2}} - \\frac{f\\left( {{x}_{2}} \\right)}{{{f}^{\'}}\\left( {{x}_{2}} \\right)}=0.8395=0.840\\left( 3sf \\right) \\\\ ; & {{x}_{4}}={{x}_{3}} - \\frac{f\\left( {{x}_{3}} \\right)}{{{f}^{\'}}\\left( {{x}_{3}} \\right)}=0.8393=0.839\\left( 3sf \\right) \\\\ ; & {{x}_{5}}={{x}_{4}} - \\frac{f\\left( {{x}_{4}} \\right)}{{{f}^{\'}}\\left( {{x}_{4}} \\right)}=0.8393=0.839\\left( 3sf \\right) \\\\ ; & f\\left( 0.839+0.0005 \\right)=0.0012>0 \\\\ ; & f\\left( 0.839-0.0005 \\right)=-0.0043<0 \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;Correct to 3 significant figures, $$\\alpha =0.839$$'),
('200303003010','(i) Let $$\\frac{5}{( x^2  + 1 )( x + 2 )} \\equiv \\frac{Ax + B}{( x^2  + 1 )} + \\frac{C}{( x + 2 )}$$;Clearing the fractions:;$$ 5 \\equiv (Ax + B)(x + 2) + C( x^2  + 1 )$$;$$ = (A + C)x^2 + (2A + B)x + (2B + C)$$;Cover - up rule:;$$x = -2$$: $$C = \\frac{5}{(-2)^2 + 1} = 1$$;Comparing coefficients:;$$x^2 : 0 = A + C$$;$$\\Rightarrow 0 = A + 1   \\Rightarrow  A = -1$$;$$x^0 : 5 = 2B + C$$;$$\\Rightarrow  5 = 2B + 1  \\Rightarrow B = 2$$;$$\\therefore \\frac{5}{( x^2  + 1 )( x + 2 )} \\equiv \\frac{2 - x}{( x^2  + 1 )} + \\frac{1}{( x + 2 )}$$ (ans);;(ii) $$\\frac{5}{( x^2  + 1 )( x + 2 )}$$;$$\\equiv \\frac{2 - x}{( x^2  + 1 )} + \\frac{1}{( x + 2 )}$$;$$ = (2 - x)(1 + x^2)^{-1} + (2 + x)^{-1}$$;$$ = (2 - x)(1 + x^2)^{-1} + \\frac{1}{2}(1 + \\frac{1}{2}x)^{-1}$$;$$ = (2 - x)(1 + x^2 + ... ) + \\frac{1}{2}(1 - \\frac{1}{2}x + \\frac{1}{4}x^2 + ... )$$;$$ = (2 - x - 2x^2 + ... ) + (\\frac{1}{2} - \\frac{1}{4}x + \\frac{1}{8}x^2 + ... )$$;$$ = \\frac{5}{2} - \\frac{5}{4}x - \\frac{15}{8}x^2 + ...$$ (ans)'),
('200303003011','Let $${P}_{n}$$ denotes $$\\sum \\limits_{r = 1}^{n} ( r - 1 )( r + 1 ) = \\frac{1}{6}n( n - 1 )( 2n + 5 )$$;For $$n = 1$$,;$$LHS = (1 - 1)(1 + 1) = 0$$;$$RHS = \\frac{1}{6}(1)(1 - 1)(2(1) + 5) = 0 = LHS$$;$$\\therefore {P}_{1}$$ is true.;;Assume $${P}_{k}$$ is true for $$k \\in \\mathbb{z^{+}}$$,;i.e $$\\sum \\limits_{r = 1}^{k} ( r - 1 )( r + 1 ) = \\frac{1}{6}k( k - 1 )( 2k + 5 )$$;$$For n = k+1$$,;$$RHS =  \\frac{1}{6}(k + 1)[( k + 1) - 1 ][ 2(k + 1) + 5 ]$$;$$LHS = \\sum \\limits_{r = 1}^{k+1} ( r - 1 )( r + 1 )$$;$$ = \\sum \\limits_{r = 1}^{k} ( r - 1 )( r + 1 ) + [(k + 1) - 1][(k + 1) + 1]$$;$$ = \\frac{1}{6}k( k - 1 )( 2k + 5 ) + k(k + 2)$$;$$ = \\frac{1}{6}k[( k - 1 )( 2k + 5 ) + 6(k + 2)]$$;$$  =\\frac{1}{6}k[2k^2 + 3k -5 + 6k + 12 ]$$;$$ = \\frac{1}{6}k [2k^2 + 9k + 7]$$;$$ = \\frac{1}{6}k(2k + 7)(k + 1)$$;$$ = \\frac{1}{6}(k+1)[(k+1)-1][2(k+1) + 5] = RHS$$;$$\\therefore {P}_{k+1}$$ is true if $${P}_{k}$$ is true.;Therefore by mathematical induction, $${P}_{n}$$ is true for all $$n \\in \\mathbb{z^{+}}$$. (ans);;$$\\sum \\limits_{r = 1}^{n} ( r - 1 )( r + 1 )$$;$$equiv \\sum \\limits_{r = 1}^{n} ( r^2 - 1 ) = \\sum \\limits_{r = 1}^{n} r^2 - \\sum\\limits_{r = 1}^{n}1 = \\sum \\limits_{r = 1}^{n} r^2 - n$$;$$\\therefore \\sum \\limits_{r = 1}^{n} r^2 = \\sum \\limits_{r = 1}^{n} ( r - 1 )( r + 1 ) + n$$;$$ = \\frac{1}{6}n( n - 1 )( 2n + 5 ) + n$$;$$ = \\frac{1}{6}n[( n - 1 )( 2n + 5 ) + 6]$$;$$ = \\frac{1}{6}n[2n^2 + 3n - 5 + 6]$$;$$ = \\frac{1}{6}n[2n^2 + 3n + 1]$$;$$ = \\frac{1}{6}n(n+1)(2n + 1)$$ (ans)'),
