('200304003026','Let $${n}_{x}$$ = sample size of X = 20;Let $${p}_{x}$$ = P(success) of X = 0.4;Let $${q}_{x} = 1 - {p}_{x} = 0 .6$$;$$X \\sim B({n}_{x}, {p}_{x})$$;Since $${n}_{x}$$ ( =20) is quite large, $${n}_{x}{p}_{x} = 8 > 5$$ and $${n}_{x}{q}_{x} = 12 > 5$$,;$$X \\sim N({n}_{x}{p}_{x}, {n}_{x}{p}_{x}{q}_{x})$$ approximately;;Let $${n}_{y}$$ = sample size of Y = 30;Let $${p}_{y}$$ = P(success) of Y = 0.6;Let $${q}_{y} = 1 - {p}_{y} = 0.4$$;$$Y \\sim B({n}_{y}{p}_{y} , {n}_{y}{p}_{y}{q}_{y})$$ approximately;;Let $$Z = Y - X$$;Let $$\\mu = E ( Z ) = E ( Y - X )$$ ;$$ = E(Y) - E(X) = {n}_{y}{p}_{y} - {n}_{x}{p}_{x}$$ ;$$ = ( 30 ) ( 0.6 ) - ( 20 ) ( 0.4 ) = 10 $$;Let $$ \\sigma^2 = Var(Z) = Var(Y - X)$$ ;$$ = Var ( Y ) + Var ( X )$$ ;$$ = {n}_{y}{p}_{y}{q}_{y} + {n}_{x}{p}_{x}{q}_{x}$$ ;$$ = ( 30 ) ( 0.6 ) ( 0.4 ) + ( 20 ) ( 0.4 ) ( 0.6 ) = 12$$ ;$$ Z \\sim N(\\mu, \\sigma^2)$$ ;$$ \\equiv Y - X \\sim N ( 10 , 12 )$$ (ans) ;;$$P ( Y - X > 13 )$$ ;$$ \\equiv P(Z > 13) = P ( Z > 13.5 )$$ ;$$ = P(z > \\frac{13.5 - \\mu}{\\sigma}) = P(z > \\frac{13.5 - 10}{\\sqrt{12}})$$ ;$$ = P ( z > 1.0104 )$$ ;$$ = 1 - \\Phi(1.010) = 1 - 0.8438$$ ;$$  0.1562 = 0.156$$ (ans)'),
('200304003027','Answer:;Let $$\\mu$$ = E(X) = 1;Let $$\\sigma^2$$ = Var(X) = 20;$$X ~ N(\\mu,\\sigma^2)$$;;(i) $$P ( X < a ) = 2P ( X > a )$$ ;$$ P(X < a) = 2 [ 1 - P(X < a) ] $$;$$ 3P ( X < a ) = 2$$ ;$$ P(X < a) = \\frac{2}{3}$$;$$ P ( z < \\frac{a - \\mu}{\\sigma} ) = \\frac{2}{3} \\equiv \\Phi ( \\frac{a - \\mu}{\\sigma} ) = \\frac{2}{3}$$ ;$$ \\frac{a - \\mu}{\\sigma}= \\Phi^{- 1}(\\frac{2}{3}) = 0.431$$ ;$$ a = \\mu + 0.431\\sigma = ( 1 ) + 0.431\\sqrt{20}$$ ;$$ = 2.927 = 2.93$$ (ans);;(ii) Let  $$\\overline{x}$$ = sample mean of n observations;$$\\overline{x} \\sim N ( \\mu , \\sigma^2 / n )$$ ;$$ P(\\overline{x} > 1.5) \\leq 0.01$$ ;$$ \\equiv P ( \\overline{x} < 1.5 ) > 1 - 0.01 = 0.99$$ ;;$$ \\Rightarrow P(z < \\frac{1.5 - \\mu}{\\sigma/\\sqrt{n}}) > 0.99 \\equiv \\Phi ( \\frac{1.5 - \\mu}{\\sigma / \\sqrt{n}} ) > 0.99$$ ;$$ \\frac{1.5 - \\mu}{\\sigma/\\sqrt{n}}> \\Phi^{- 1}(0.99) = 2.326 $$;$$ \\sqrt{n} = \\frac{2.326\\sigma}{1.5 - \\mu} = \\frac{2.326\\sqrt{20}}{1.5 - 1} = 20.80 $$;$$ n >(20.80)^2 = 432.64$$;;$$\\therefore P (\\overline{x} > 1.5 ) \\leq 0.01, n \\geq 433$$ (ans)'),
('200304003028','Let $$X$$ = no. of sports cars served in 1 hr;$$X \\sim Po(2)$$;Let Y = no. of motor-cycles served in 1 hr ;$$Y \\sim Po(1)$$;Let $$Z$$ = no. of sports cars and motor-cycles served in a randomly chosen period of 2 hr ;$$     = {X}_{1} + {X}_{2} + {Y}_{1} + {Y}_{2}$$;where $${X}_{i}$$ = independent observations of X;     $${Y}_{i}$$ = independent observations of Y;Let $$\\lambda = E(Z) = E({X}_{1} + {X}_{2} + {Y}_{1} + {Y}_{2})$$;$$      = 2E(X) + 2E(Y) = 2(2) + 2(1) = 6$$;;$$Z \\sim P0(\\lambda)$$;$$P ( Z \\geq 4 )$$ ;$$ = 1 - P(Z \\leq 3)$$ ;$$ = 1 - [ P ( Z = 0 ) + P ( Z = 1 ) + P ( Z = 2 ) + P ( Z = 3 ) ]$$ ;$$ = 1 - e^{- \\lambda}[ \\frac{\\lambda^0}{0 !}+ \\frac{\\lambda^1}{1 !}+ \\frac{\\lambda^2}{2 !}+ \\frac{\\lambda^3}{3 !}] $$;$$ = 1 - e^{- 6} [ 1 + 6 + \\frac{6^2}{2 !} + \\frac{6^3}{3 !} ]$$;$$ = 0.8487 = 0.849$$ (ans);;Let $$C$$ = cost of petrol supplied to sport cars;$$C \\sim U ( 10 , 100 )$$ ;$$ \\Rightarrow E(C) = \\frac{1}{2}(10 + 100) = 55 $$;$$ \\Rightarrow Var ( C ) = \\frac{1}{12} ( 100 - 10 )^2 = 675 $$;;Let $$D$$ = cost of petrol supplied to motor cycle;$$D \\sim U ( 5 , 35 )$$ ;$$ \\Rightarrow E(D) = \\frac{1}{2}(5 + 35) = 20$$ ;$$ \\Rightarrow Var ( D ) = \\frac{1}{12} ( 35 - 5 )^2 = 75$$;Let $$T$$ = cost of petrol supplied to a random sample consisting of 4 cars and 2 motor cycles;$$ = {C}_{1} + {C}_{2} + {C}_{3} + {C}_{4} + {D}_{1} + {D}_{2}$$;where $${C}_{i}$$ = independent observations of C;     $${D}_{i}$$ = independent observations of D;;$$ E(T)  = E({C}_{1} + {C}_{2} + {C}_{3} + {C}_{4} + {D}_{1} + {D}_{2})$$ ;$$ = 4E ( C ) + 2E ( D )$$ ;$$ = 4(55) + 2(20) = 260$$ (ans); ;$$ Var ( T ) = Var ( {C}_{1} + {C}_{2} + {C}_{3} + {C}_{4} + {D}_{1} + {D}_{2} )$$ ;$$ = 4Var(C) + 2Var(D)$$ ;$$ = 4 ( 675 ) + 2 ( 75 ) = 2850$$ (ans)'),
('200304003029','Let $$n$$ = sample size = 80;Let $$\\mu = E(x)$$;Let $$\\sigma^2 = Var(x)$$;$$\\hat{\\mu} = \\overline{x} = \\frac{\\sum x}{n} = \\frac{79.53}{80} = 0.9941$$ ;$$ \\hat{\\sigma}^2 = \\frac{1}{n - 1}[ \\sum x^2 - \\frac{1}{n}(\\sum x)^2 ]$$ ;$$ = \\frac{1}{79} [ 100.4621 - \\frac{1}{80} ( 79.53 )^2 ] = 0.2709$$;;Let $$\\mu_{0}$$ = required mean = 1.10kg;Test $${H}_{0}: \\mu = \\mu_{0}$$ against $${H}_{1} : \\mu < \\mu_{0}$$ a 1 tailed test for less;The 4% critical value, $${z}_{0.04} = 1.751$$ ;Reject $${H}_{0}$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \\frac{\\overline{x} - \\mu_{0}}{\\hat{\\sigma} / \\sqrt{n}} = \\frac{0.9941 - 1.10}{\\sqrt{0.2709 / 80}} = - 1.819$$;Since $$z < - {z}_{0.04}$$, reject $${H}_{0}$$ and conclude that, at 4% level of significance, there is sufficient evidence that the mean mass of the contents is less than 1.10 kg.;;Alternative test is :;Test $${H}_{0}: \\mu = \\mu_{0}$$ against $${H}_{1} : \\mu \\neq \\mu_{0}$$ a 2 tailed test for difference;At 4% significance level, critical value $${z}_{0.02} = 2.054$$;$${H}_{0}$$ is rejected if $$| z | > |{z}_{0.02}|$$;$$\\lvert \\frac{\\overline{x} - \\mu_0}{\\hat{\\sigma} / \\sqrt{n}} \\lvert > 2.054$$ ;$$ \\lvert \\overline{x} - \\mu_0 \\lvert > 2.054 \\hat{\\sigma}/\\sqrt{n}$$;$$ \\lvert 0.9941 - \\mu_0 \\lvert > 2.054\\sqrt{0.2709 / 80} = 0.1195$$ ;$$ 0.9941 - \\mu_0 < - 0.1195 $$ or $$ 0.9941 - \\mu_0 > 0.1195$$ ;;$$ \\mu_0 > 1.1136$$ or  $$\\mu_0 < 0.8746$$ (ans)'),
('200304003030','Let $$\\lambda = E(X) = 60p$$;$$X \\sim B(60, q)$$ and $$X \\sim Po(\\lambda )$$ approximately;$$\\Rightarrow 60p < 5 \\Rightarrow p < \\frac{5}{60} \\Rightarrow p < \\frac{1}{12}$$ (ans);;$$X \\sim Po(\\lambda )$$ approximately;$$P(X = 0) = 0.25$$;$$\\Rightarrow e^{-\\lambda } = 0.25 \\Rightarrow \\lambda = 1.386 = 1.39$$ ;$$P( X \\leq 2)$$;$$ = P(X = 0) + P(X = 1) + P(X = 2)$$;$$ = e^{-\\lambda}[\\frac{\\lambda^0}{0!} + \\frac{\\lambda^1}{1!} + \\frac{\\lambda^2}{2!}]$$;$$ = 0.25 [1 + 1.386 + \\frac{(1.386)^2}{2}]$$;$$ = 0.8366 = 0.837$$ (ans);;$$P(X = 3) = e^{-\\lambda}\\frac{\\lambda^3}{3!} = e^{-1.386}\\frac{(1.386)^3}{6} = 0.1110$$;$$\\lambda = 60p = 1.386 \\Rightarrow p = 0.0231$$;Let $$Y$$ = no. of infected peaches out of 15;$$ q = 1 - p = 0.9769$$;$$Y = B(15, p)$$;$$P(Y = 0 or Y = 1)$$;$$ = P(Y = 0) + P(Y = 1)$$;$$ = {q}^{15} + {}^{15}{C}_{1}pq^{14}$$;$$ = (0.9769)^{15} + {}^{15}{C}_{1}(0.0231)(0.9769)^{14}$$;$$ = 0.9541$$;;P(production accepted as satisfactory);$$ = P(X \\leq 2) + P(X=3) \\cdot P(Y = 0 or Y= 1)$$;$$ = 0.8366 + (0.1110)(0.9541)$$;$$ = 0.9425 = 0.943$$ (ans)'),
