('200403003013','Let $$\\frac{9{{x}^{2}}}{{{\\left( x-1 \\right)}^{2}}\\left( x+2 \\right)}\\equiv \\frac{A}{x-1}+\\frac{B}{{{\\left( x-1 \\right)}^{2}}}+\\frac{C}{x+2}$$;Clearing the fractions:;$$\\begin{align};  & 9{{x}^{2}}\\equiv A\\left( x-1 \\right)\\left( x+2 \\right)+B\\left( x+2 \\right)+C{{\\left( x-1 \\right)}^{2}} \\\\ ; & =\\left( A+C \\right){{x}^{2}}+\\left( A+B-2C \\right)x+\\left( -2A+2B+C \\right) \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;Cover-up rule:;$$\\begin{align};  & x=-2:C=4 \\\\ ; & x=1:B=3 \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;Comparing coefficients:;$$\\begin{align};  & {{x}^{2}}:9=A+C \\\\ ; & \\Rightarrow A=5 \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore \\frac{9{{x}^{2}}}{{{\\left( x-1 \\right)}^{2}}\\left( x+2 \\right)}\\equiv \\frac{5}{x-1}+\\frac{3}{{{\\left( x-1 \\right)}^{2}}}+\\frac{4}{x+2}$$;;$$\\begin{align};  & \\therefore \\int\\limits_{2}^{3}{\\frac{9{{x}^{2}}}{{{\\left( x-1 \\right)}^{2}}\\left( x+2 \\right)}dx}\\equiv \\int\\limits_{2}^{3}{\\left( \\frac{5}{x-1}+\\frac{3}{{{\\left( x-1 \\right)}^{2}}}+\\frac{4}{x+2} \\right)dx} \\\\ ; & =\\left[ 5\\ln \\left( x-1 \\right)-\\frac{3}{x-1}+4\\ln \\left( x+2 \\right) \\right]_{2}^{3} \\\\ ; & =5\\ln 2-\\frac{3}{2}+4\\ln 5-5\\ln 1+3-4\\ln 4 \\\\ ; & =\\frac{3}{2}4\\ln 5+5\\ln 2-4\\ln {{2}^{2}} \\\\ ; & =\\frac{3}{2}4\\ln 5-3\\ln 2 \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;'),
('200403003014','$$\\begin{align};  & y=\\frac{{{x}^{3}}}{{{\\left( x+1 \\right)}^{2}}} \\\\ ; & \\frac{dy}{dx}=\\frac{d}{dx}\\left[ \\frac{{{x}^{3}}}{{{\\left( x+1 \\right)}^{2}}} \\right]=\\frac{{{\\left( x+1 \\right)}^{2}}\\left( 2{{x}^{2}} \\right)-\\left( {{x}^{3}} \\right)2\\left( x+1 \\right)}{{{\\left( x+1 \\right)}^{4}}} \\\\ ; & =\\frac{2{{x}^{2}}\\left( x+1 \\right)\\left( x+1-x \\right)}{{{\\left( x+1 \\right)}^{4}}} \\\\ ; & =\\frac{2{{x}^{2}}\\left( x+1 \\right)}{{{\\left( x+1 \\right)}^{4}}}=\\frac{2{{x}^{2}}}{{{\\left( x+1 \\right)}^{3}}} \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;;At stationary pts, $$\\frac{dy}{dx}=0$$;$$\\begin{align};  & \\Rightarrow \\frac{2{{x}^{2}}}{{{\\left( x+1 \\right)}^{3}}}=0 \\\\ ; & \\Rightarrow x=0 \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;$$\\begin{align};  & x={{0}^{-}},\\frac{dy}{dx}=\\frac{2{{x}^{2}}}{{{\\left( x+1 \\right)}^{3}}}>0 \\\\ ; & x=0+,\\frac{dy}{dx}=\\frac{2{{x}^{2}}}{{{\\left( x+1 \\right)}^{3}}}>0 \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;At x = 0, the stationary pt is a point of inflexion.;'),
('200403003015','$$\\begin{align};  & \\frac{dy}{dx}+y=x{{y}^{3}}\\equiv \\frac{1}{{{y}^{3}}}\\frac{dy}{dx}+\\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}=x} \\\\ ; & z=\\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}},\\frac{dz}{dx}=\\frac{d}{dx}\\left[ \\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}} \\right]=-\\frac{2}{{{y}^{3}}}\\frac{dy}{dx} \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;Subst $$\\frac{1}{{{y}^{3}}}\\frac{dy}{dx}$$ and $$\\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}}$$ into $$\\frac{1}{{{y}^{3}}}\\frac{dy}{dx}+\\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}}=x$$:;$$\\begin{align};  & -\\frac{1}{2}\\frac{dz}{dx}+z=x \\\\ ; & \\therefore \\frac{dz}{dx}-2z=-2x\\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;;With $$z=\\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}}$$,;$$\\frac{dy}{dx}+y=x{{y}^{3}}\\equiv \\frac{dz}{dx}-2z=-2x$$;Let $$h\\left( x \\right)=\\int{\\left( -2 \\right)dx}=-2x$$ ;$$\\Rightarrow$$ integrating factor = $${{e}^{h\\left( x \\right)}}={{e}^{-2x}}$$ and $${{e}^{-h\\left( x \\right)}}={{e}^{2x}}$$;;General solution is:;$$\\begin{align};  & z={{e}^{-h\\left( x \\right)}}\\left[ \\int{{{e}^{h\\left( x \\right)}}\\left( -2x \\right)dx}+c \\right] \\\\ ; & ={{e}^{2x}}\\left[ {{e}^{-2x}}x-\\int{{{e}^{-2x}}dx}+c \\right] \\\\ ; & ={{e}^{2x}}\\left[ {{e}^{-2x}}x+\\frac{1}{2}{{e}^{-2x}}+c \\right] \\\\ ; & =x+\\frac{1}{2}+c{{e}^{2x}} \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};  & \\equiv \\frac{1}{{{y}^{2}}}=\\frac{1}{2}+x+c{{e}^{2x}} \\\\ ; & i.e. \\\\ ; & \\left( \\frac{1}{2}+x+c{{e}^{2x}} \\right){{y}^{2}}=1 \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;;At x = 0, $$y=\\sqrt{2}$$;$$\\begin{align};  & \\Rightarrow \\left( \\frac{1}{2}+0+c{{e}^{0}} \\right)\\left( 2 \\right)=1 \\\\ ; & \\Rightarrow 1+2c=1\\Rightarrow c=0 \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;Particular solution is ;$$\\begin{align};  & \\left( \\frac{1}{2}+x \\right){{y}^{2}}=1 \\\\ ; & \\Rightarrow y=\\sqrt{\\frac{2}{1+2x}} \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$'),
('200403003016','$$\\begin{align};\\overrightarrow{AB} = \\overrightarrow{OB} - \\overrightarrow{OA} = \\begin{pmatrix};13\\\\ 9\\\\ \\alpha \\end{pmatrix} - \\begin{pmatrix} 9\\\\ 3\\\\ 26 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 4\\\\ 6\\\\\\alpha -26\\end{pmatrix};\\end{align}$$;;An equation of line M through A and B is M: $$r  = \\overrightarrow{OA} + s \\overrightarrow{AB}, s\\in\\mathbb{R}$$;$$\\begin{align};=  \\begin{pmatrix} 9\\\\ 3\\\\ 26 \\end{pmatrix} + s \\begin{pmatrix} 4\\\\ 6\\\\\\alpha -26\\end{pmatrix};\\end{align}$$;;Lines L and M intersect at P;$$\\begin{align} ;\\Rightarrow \\overrightarrow{OP} =  \\begin{pmatrix} 9\\\\ 3\\\\ 26 \\end{pmatrix} + s \\begin{pmatrix} 4\\\\ 6\\\\\\alpha -26\\end{pmatrix} = + s \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\ 3\\\\ 7 \\end{pmatrix} + t \\begin{pmatrix} 2\\\\ -1\\\\5\\end{pmatrix};\\end{align}$$ ;for some s, $$t \\in\\mathbb{R}$$;;Equating components:;$$\\begin{align};& 9 + 4s = 1 + 2t &----(1)\\\\;& 3 + 6s = 3 - t &----(2)\\\\;& 26 + (\\alpha-26)s = 7 + 5t & ----(3)\\\\;\\end{align}$$;;Eqn(1) + 2 x (2):;$$15 +16s =7 \\Rightarrow s = -\\frac{1}{2}$$;Subst $$s = -\\frac{1}{2}$$ into Eqn(2):;$$3+6(-\\frac{1}{2}) = 3 - t \\Rightarrow t=3 $$;Subst $$s = -\\frac{1}{2}$$ and t=3 into Eqn(3):;$$26 +(\\alpha - 26)(-\\frac{1}{2})=7 + 5(3)$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\alpha = 34$$;;$$\\overrightarrow{AB} = \\begin{pmatrix} 4\\\\ 6\\\\ 34-26 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 4\\\\ 6\\\\ 8 \\end{pmatrix}$$;;Let $$\\theta$$ = acute angle between lines L and AB;$$\\begin{align};& \\Rightarrow \\left| \\begin{pmatrix} 2\\\\ -1\\\\ 5 \\end{pmatrix} - \\begin{pmatrix} 4\\\\ 6\\\\ 8 \\end{pmatrix}\\right| = \\left| \\begin{pmatrix} 2\\\\ -1\\\\ 5 \\end{pmatrix} \\right| - \\left| \\begin{pmatrix} 4\\\\ 6\\\\ 8 \\end{pmatrix} \\right| \\cos{\\theta} \\\\;&\\Rightarrow |(2)(4) + (-1)(6) + (5)(8)| = \\sqrt{2^{2} + (-1)^{2} + 5^{2}} \\sqrt{4^{2} + 6^{2} + 8^{2}}\\cos{\\theta}\\\\;&\\cos{\\theta} = 0.7120\\\\;& \\therefore \\theta = \\cos^{-1}(0.7120) = 44.60 = 44.6^{\\circ} (1dp);\\end{align}$$;;Q is on L;$$\\begin{align};& \\Rightarrow \\overrightarrow{OQ} = \\begin{pmatrix} 1\\\\ 3\\\\ 7 \\end{pmatrix} + \\begin{pmatrix} 2\\\\ -1\\\\ 5 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 1+2t \\\\ 3-t\\\\ t+5t \\end{pmatrix} for some t \\in \\mathbb{R}\\\\;& \\overrightarrow{CQ} = \\overrightarrow{OQ} - \\overrightarrow{OC} = \\begin{pmatrix} 1+2t \\\\ 3-t\\\\ t+5t \\end{pmatrix} - \\begin{pmatrix} 2\\\\ 5\\\\ 1 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} -1+2t\\\\ -2-t\\\\ 6+5t \\end{pmatrix};\\end{align}$$;$$\\overrightarrow{CQ}$$ is perpendicular to  L;$$\\begin{align};\\Rightarrow \\begin{pmatrix} -1+2t\\\\ -2-t\\\\ 6+5t \\end{pmatrix} . \\begin{pmatrix} 2\\\\ -1\\\\ 5 \\end{pmatrix} = 0 \\\\;\\end{align}$$;img'),
('200404003001','Let $$\\angle$$PXQ = $$\\theta$$;Sine rule on $$\\Delta$$PQX:;$$\\frac{x}{\\sin{\\alpha}} = \\frac{\\lambda}{\\sin{\\theta}} \\Rightarrow x = \\frac{\\lambda \\sin{\\alpha}}{\\sin{\\theta}}$$;Sine rule on $$\\Delta$$PXR:;$$\\frac{y}{\\sin{\\alpha}} = \\frac{\\mu}{\\sin{(\\pi-\\theta)}} \\equiv \\frac{\\mu}{\\sin{\\theta}}\\Rightarrow y = \\frac{\\mu\\sin{\\alpha}}{\\sin{\\theta}}$$;$$\\therefore \\frac{\\left(\\frac{\\lambda \\sin{\\alpha}}{\\sin{\\theta}}\\right)}{\\left(\\frac{\\mu\\sin{\\alpha}}{\\sin{\\theta}}\\right)} = \\frac{a}{b} = \\frac{\\lambda}{\\mu}$$'),
('200404003002','Let a = $$1^{st}$$ term of G.P.;Let r = common ratio of G.P.;Let $$T_i$$ = $$i^{th}$$ term of G.P. (= $$ar^{i-1}$$);;Population at end of 1995 ($$T_1$$) = 46650;$$\\Rightarrow a = 46650$$;;Population at end of 2000 ($$T_6$$) = 54200;$$\\Rightarrow ar^{5}$$ = 54200;;$$\\begin{align};i.e. \\\\;&(46650)r^{5} = 54200 \\\\;& r^{5} = 1.1618 \\\\;&\\therefore r = 1.030;\\end{align}$$;;(i) Population at end of 2006,;$$T_{12} = ar^{11} = (46650)(1.030)^{11} = 64574 = 64570(4 sf)$$;;(ii) Let n = year in which the population reaches 100000;$$\\begin{align};& T_n = ar^{n-1} > 100000 \\\\;& \\Rightarrow (46650)(1.030)^{n-1} > 100000\\\\;& (1.030)^{n-1} > 2.143\\\\;& n-1 > \\frac{\\ln{2.143}}{\\ln{1.030}} = 25.78\\\\;& n > 26.78\\\\;&\\therefore n=27 ;\\end{align}$$'),
('200404003003','For all values of x,;6x + 16 = A (2x + 4) + B; 6x +16 = 2Ax + 4A + B;$$\\Rightarrow $$ 6x = 2Ax, $$\\therefore$$ A = 3;$$\\Rightarrow$$ if A = 3,  4A + B = 4(3) + B, $$\\therefore$$ B = 4;;$$\\begin{align};& \\int_{-2}^{1} \\frac{6x + 16}{x^{2} + 4x + 13} dx \\\\;& = \\int_{-2}^{1} \\frac{3(2x+4) + 4}{x^{2} + 4x + 13} dx \\\\;& = 3\\int_{-2}^{1} \\frac{2x+4}{x^{2} + 4x + 13} dx + 4 \\int_{-2}^{1} \\frac{1}{x^{2} + 4x + 13}dx \\\\;& = 3[\\ln{(x^{2} + 4 + 13)}]_{-2}^{1} + 4 \\int_{-2}^{1} \\frac{1}{(x+2)^2 + 3^2}dx \\\\;& = 3[\\ln{(18)} - \\ln{(9)}] + \\frac{4}{3}[\\tan^{-1}{\\frac{x+2}{3}}]_{-2}^{1}\\\\;& = 3\\ln{\\left(\\frac{18}{9}\\right)} + \\frac{4}{3}[\\tan^{-1}{(1)} - \\tan^{-1}{(0)}]\\\\;& = 3\\ln{2} + \\frac{4}{3}\\left[\\frac{1}{4}\\pi -0\\right]\\\\;& = 3\\ln{2} + \\frac{1}{3}\\pi ;\\end{align}$$'),
('200404003004','No. of ways to place 10 canisters on 10 bases;= ^{10}\\textrm{P}_{10} = 10! = 3 628 800;;(i) No. of ways to place 2 particular canisters on remaining 6 bases (not A, E, F or J);= ^{6}\\textrm{P}_{2} = \\frac{6!}{(6-2)!} = 30;No. of ways to place remaining 8 canisters on remaining 8 bases;= ^{8}\\textrm{P}_{8} = 8! = 40 320;$$\\therefore$$ No. of ways to place the canisters ;= 30 x 40 320 = 1 209 600;;(ii) ;Case 1:;1st particular canisters is placed in one of 4 corner bases (A, E, F or J),;2nd particular canisters can be placed in any of 8 bases (not next to the 1st on the same side);No. of ways to place remaining 8 canisters on remaining 8 bases = 40 320;$$\\therefore$$ No. of ways to place the canisters; = 4 x 8 x 40 320 = 1 290 240;;Case 2:;1st particular canisters is placed in one of 6 non-corner bases (not A, E, F or J),;2nd particular canisters can be placed in any of 7 bases (not next to the 1st on the same side);No. of ways to place remaining 8 canisters on remaining 8 bases = 40 320;$$\\therefore$$ No. of ways to place the canisters; = 6 x 7 x 40 320 = 1 693 440;;$$\\therefore$$ Total no. of ways to place the canisters; = 1 290 240 + 1 693 440; = 2 983 680'),
('200404003005','a) $$f(\\theta) = \\sin^{2}{\\theta} - 6 \\sin{\\theta} + 4 \\equiv (\\sin{\\theta} - 3)^{2} - 5$$;Deduce that $$f(\\theta)$$ is greatest when $$ \\sin{\\theta = -1} \\equiv (\\sin{\\theta} -3) = -4$$;i.e. $$f(\\theta)_{greatest} = (-4)^{2} -5 = 11$$;Deduce that $$f(\\theta)$$ is least when $$\\sin{\\theta} = 1 \\equiv (\\sin{\\theta} -3) = -2$$;i.e. $$f(\\theta)_{least} = (-2)^{2} -5 = -1$$;;b) ;$$\\begin{align} &\\sin{(A+B)} = 2 \\cos{(A-B)}\\\\;& \\Rightarrow \\sin{A} \\cos{B} + \\cos{A}\\sin{B} = 2(\\cos{A}\\cos{B} + \\sin{A}\\sin{B}) \\\\;&\\equiv \\frac{\\sin{A} \\cos{B}}{\\cos{A}\\cos{B} } + \\frac{\\cos{A}\\sin{B} }{\\cos{A}\\cos{B} } = 2\\left(1+\\frac{ \\sin{A}\\sin{B}}{\\cos{A}\\cos{B}}\\right)\\\\;& \\tan{A} + \\tan{B} = 2 + 2 \\tan{A}\\tan{B}\\\\;& \\frac{1}{3} + \\tan{B} = 2 + \\frac{2}{3} \\tan{B}\\\\;& \\left(1-\\frac{2}{3}\\right)\\tan{B} = 2 - \\frac{1}{3}\\\\;&\\therefore \\tan{B} = 5;\\end{align}$$'),
('200404003023','Given $$P(A \\cup B)$$ = 0.9, $$P(A \\cap B)$$ = 0.2, and P(A|B) = 0.8.;;$$\\begin{align};& P(A \\cap B) = P(A | B).P(B) \\\\;& i.e. 0.2 = 0.8 P(B) \\\\;& \\Rightarrow P(B) = 0.25 \\\\;& P ( A \\cup B ) = P ( A ) + P ( B ) - P ( A \\cap B ) \\\\;& i.e. 0.9 = P(A) + 0.25 - 0.2 \\\\;& \\therefore P ( A ) = 0.85 \\\\;& P(B \\prime) = 1 - P(B) = 1 - 0.25 = 0.75\\\\;\\end{align}$$'),
('200404003024','X~N($$\\mu$$,$$\\sigma^2$$);;As normal distribution are symmetrical,P ( X < 10 ) = P ( X > 20 ) ;$$\\begin{align};& \\Rightarrow \\mu(10 + 20)/2 = 15 \\\\ ;& P ( X > 20 ) = 0.330 \\\\ ;& \\equiv P(X < 20) = 1 - 0.330 = 0.669 \\\\ ;& \\equiv P ( Z < \\frac{20 - 15}{\\sigma^2} ) = 0.669 \\\\ ;& \\Phi(\\frac{20 - 15}{\\sigma^2}) = 0.669 \\\\ ;& \\frac{20 - 15}{\\sigma^2} = \\Phi^{- 1} ( 0.669 ) = 0.437 \\\\ ;& \\sigma^2 = \\frac{20 - 15}{0.437}= 11.44 \\\\ ;& \\therefore \\sigma = 3.382 = 3.38 (3sf) \\\\;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};& E ( \\overline{X}) = E ( X ) = \\mu = 15 \\\\;& Var(\\overline{X}) = \\frac{Var(X)}{100}= \\frac{\\sigma^2}{100}= \\frac{11.44}{100} \\\\;& = 0.1144 = 0.114 (3sf);\\end{align}$$'),
('200404003025','Let X = mass of an apple of variety A;Let Y = mass of an apple of variety B;X ~ N(0.125,0.022), Y ~ N(0.100,0.032);Let C = $$(X_{1}+ X_{2}+ X_{3}) + (Y_{1}+ Y_{2}+ Y_{3}+ Y_{4})$$;where $$X_{1}, X_{2}, X_{3}$$ are masses of 3 randomly chosen apples of variety A, and $$Y_{1}, Y_{2}, Y_{3}, Y_{4}$$ are masses of 4 randomly chosen apples of variety B.;$$\\begin{align};&Let \\mu_c = E (C) \\\\ ;&= E((X_1 + X_2 + X_3) -(Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4)) \\\\ ;&= 3E ( X ) - 4E ( Y ) \\\\ ;&= 3(0.125) - 4(0.100) = - 0.025 \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};&Let \\sigma_c^2 = Var ( C ) \\\\ ;&= Var((X_1 + X_2 + X_3) -(Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4)) \\\\ ;&= 3Var ( X ) + 4Var ( Y ) \\\\ ;&= 3({0.02}^2) + 4({0.03}^2) = 0.0048 \\\\;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};&C \\sim N ( \\mu_c , \\sigma_c^2 ) \\\\ ;&P((X_1 + X_2 + X_3) >(Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4)) \\\\ ;&\\equiv P ( ( X_1 + X_2 + X_3 ) - ( Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4 ) > 0 ) \\\\ ;&\\equiv P(C > 0) \\\\ ;&\\equiv P ( Z > \\frac{0 - \\mu_c}{\\sigma_c} ) = P ( Z > \\frac{0 - ( - 0.025 )}{\\sqrt{0.0048}} ) \\\\ ;&= P(Z > 0.3608) \\equiv 1 - \\Phi(0.3608) \\\\ ;&= 1 - 0.6410 = 0.3590 = 0.359 (3sf);\\end{align}$$'),
('200404003026','Let $$p_{9} = 9^{th}$$ percentile of X;$$\\begin{align};& F( p_9 ) = 0.09 \\\\;& \\frac{1}{81}(p_9)^2 = 0.09 \\\\;& \\therefore p_9 = 2.7 ;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};& f(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} F(x) \\\\;& =  \\frac{d}{dx}[\\frac{1}{81} x^2 ] \\\\;&= \\frac{2}{81}x, for 0 \\leq x \\leq 9 \\\\;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};& E (\\sqrt{X}) = \\int^\\infty_{-\\infty} \\sqrt{x}f (x)dx \\\\;& =   \\int^9_0 \\sqrt{x} \\left( \\frac{2}{81}x \\right)dx, for 0 \\leq x \\leq 9 \\\\;& =   \\int^9_0 \\frac{2}{81} x^{3 / 2}dx \\\\;& = {\\left[ \\frac{4}{405} x^{5 / 2}\\right]}^9_0   = \\frac{12}{5}\\\\;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};& E ( X ) = \\int^\\infty_{- \\infty}x.f(x) dx \\\\;& = \\int^9_0 x(\\frac{2}{81}x) dx \\\\;& = \\int^9_0 \\frac{2}{81}x^2 dx \\\\;& = {[ \\frac{2}{243} x^3 ]}^9_0 = 6 \\\\;\\end{align}$$;$$\\begin{align};& Var(\\sqrt{X}) = E(X) - [ E(\\sqrt{X}) ]^2 \\\\;& = 6 - ( \\frac{12}{5} )^2 = 0.24 \\\\;\\end{align}$$'),
('200404003027','A suitable model for the distribution of Y is uniform (or rectangular) distribution.;;Let M = total mass of batch = $$\\sum \\left(x_{i} + \\frac{y_{i}}{1000}\\right)$$;$$\\begin{align};& E(M) = E\\left[\\sum \\left(x_{i} + \\frac{y_{i}}{1000}\\right)\\right] \\\\;& =\\left(\\sum x_{i}\\right) + \\frac{E(\\sum y_{i})}{1000} \\\\;& =\\left(\\sum x_{i}\\right) + \\frac{60E(Y)}{1000} \\\\;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};& Y \\sim U (0,1000) \\\\;& \\Rightarrow E(Y) = \\frac{1}{2}(0, 1000) = 500 \\\\;& \\therefore E(M) = (\\sum x_{i} ) + \\frac{60(500)}{1000} = (\\sum x_{i} ) + 30;\\end{align}$$;;Given Var(Y) = $$\\frac{10^{6}}{12}$$;$$P(\\left(\\sum x_{i}\\right)+30$$ within $$\\pm$$ 5kg of $$\\sum \\left(x_{i} + \\frac{y_{i}}{1000}\\right))$$;$$\\equiv$$ P(30 within $$\\pm$$ 5kg of $$\\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000}$$);$$\\equiv P\\left(25 < \\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000} < 35\\right)$$;;$$\\begin{align};& Let S = \\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000} \\\\;& E(S) = E\\left(\\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000}\\right) \\\\;& = \\frac{60E(Y)}{1000} \\\\;& = \\frac{60(500)}{1000} = 30 \\\\;& Var(S) = Var\\left(\\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000}\\right) \\\\;& = \\frac{60 Var(Y)}{{1000}^2} \\\\;& = \\frac{60\\left(\\frac{{10}^6}{12}\\right)}{{10}^6}= 5 \\\\;\\end{align}$$;;Since batch size (=60) is large, S ~ N(30,5) approximately. ;$$\\begin{align};& P ( 25 < \\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000} < 35 ) \\\\;& \\equiv P(25 < S < 35) \\\\;& \\equiv P\\left(\\frac{25 - 30}{\\sqrt{5}} < Z < \\frac{35 - 30}{\\sqrt{5}}\\right) \\\\;& = P(- \\sqrt{5}< Z < \\sqrt{5}) \\equiv 2 \\Phi(\\sqrt{5}) - 1 \\\\;& = 2\\Phi ( 2.236 ) - 1 = 2 ( 0.9873 ) - 1 \\\\;& = 0.9746 = 0.975 (3sf)\\\\;\\end{align}$$'),
('200404003028','A condition is that the moths are caught at randomly scattered intervals.;;Let M = no. of moths caught in an evening ;Let $$\\lambda$$=E(M)=3.5;M ~ Po($$\\lambda$$);P(5 or more moths caught in an evening);P ( M $$\\geq$$ 5 ) ;$$\\equiv$$ 1 - P(M $$\\leq$$ 4) ;= 1 - [P(M=0) + P(M=1) + P(M=2) + P(M = 3) + P(M = 4)] ;= 1 - $$e^{- \\lambda} \\left[ \\frac{\\lambda^0}{0 !} + \\frac{\\lambda^1}{1 !} + \\frac{\\lambda^2}{2 !} + \\frac{\\lambda^3}{3 !} + \\frac{\\lambda^4}{4 !}\\right]$$ ;= 1 - $$e^{- 3.5} \\left[ 1 + 3.5 + \\frac{(3.5)^2}{2}+ \\frac{(3.5)^3}{6}+ \\frac{(3.5)^4}{24} \\right]$$ ;= 0.2746 = 0.275 (3sf);;Let B = $$M_1+M_2+M_3+M_4$$ where $$M_1, M_2, M_3, M_4$$ are no. of moths caught in 4 randomly chosen evenings. ;Let $$\\mu$$=E(B)=E($$M_1+M_2+M_3+M_4$$) = 4E(M) = 4(3.5) = 14.0;B ~ Po($$\\mu$$);Since $$\\mu$$(=14) $$\\geq$$ 10;B ~ N($$\\mu$$,$$\\mu$$) approximately;P( 18 or more caught in 4 evenings) ;P ( B $$\\geq$$ 18 ) ;$$\\equiv$$ P(B > 17.5) ;$$\\equiv$$ P$$\\left(Z > \\frac{17.5 - \\lambda}{\\sqrt{\\lambda}}\\right)$$;= P$$\\left(Z > \\frac{17.5 - 14}{\\sqrt{14}}\\right)$$;= P$$(Z > 0.9354) \\equiv 1 - \\Phi (0.935)$$;= 1 - 0.8251 = 0.175 (3sf)'),
('200404003029','a) The procedure does not gives a random sample because the children do not have equal chances of being selected.;;b) ;Let n = sample size = 50;Let $$p_0$$ = assume p = 0.8 and $$q_0$$ = 1 - $$p_0$$ = 0.2;Let $$p_s$$ = sample p = $$\\frac{34}{50}$$ = 0.68 and $$q_s$$ = 1- $$p_s$$ = 0.32;;Test $$H_0: p = p_0$$ against $$H_1: p < p_0$$ a 1 tailed test for less;The 5% critical value, $$z_{0.05}$$ = 1.645 ;Reject $$H_0$$ if $$z < -z_{0.05}$$;Under $$H_0$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \\frac{p_s - p_0}{\\sqrt{p_0 q_0 / n}} = \\frac{0.68 - 0.8}{\\sqrt{( 0.8 ) ( 0.2 ) / 50}} = - 2.12$$;Since $$z < -z_{0.05}$$, reject $$H_0$$ and conclude that at the 5% level of significance, there is sufficient evidence that the proportion of children at the school with access to a computer at home is less than 0.8.;;$$z_{0.025} \\sqrt{\\frac{p_s q_s}{n}} = 1.960\\sqrt{\\frac{( 0.68 ) ( 0.32 )}{50}} = 0.1293$$;A symmetric 95% confidence interval;$$p_s - z_{0.025} \\sqrt{\\frac{p_s q_s}{n}} , p_s + z_{0.025} \\sqrt{\\frac{p_s q_s}{n}}$$  ;= [ 0.68 - 0.1293, 0.68 + 0.1293 ] ;= [ 0.5507 , 0.8093 ] ;= [ 0.551, 0.809 ] (3sf)'),
('200404003030','(i) Tabulate all possible products:;img;Tabulate frequency / probability distribution:;img;;$$E(X) = \\sum_{all x_{i}} x_{i}.P(X = x) $$;$$= (1)\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (2)\\left(\\frac{12}{36}\\right) + (3)\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (4)\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (6)\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) $$;$$= 3$$;;$$E(X^{2}) = \\sum_{all x_{i}} {x_{i}}^{2}.P(X = x) $$;$$= (1)^{2}\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (2)^{2}\\left(\\frac{12}{36}\\right) + (3)^{2}\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (4)^{2}\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (6)^{2}\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right)$$;$$= \\frac{35}{3}$$;;$$\\therefore Var(X) = E(X^{2}) - [E(X)]^{2}$$;$$ = \\left(\\frac{35}{3}\\right) - (3)^{2} = \\frac{8}{3}$$;;(ii) ;Let n = sample size = 100;Let p = P(X = 2) = $$\\frac{12}{36}$$ = $$\\frac{1}{3}$$ and q = 1 - p = $$\\frac{2}{3}$$;T ~ B(n,p);Since n(= 100) is large and np$$\\left(= \\frac{100}{3}\\right)$$ > 5 and nq$$\\left(= \\frac{200}{3}\\right)$$ > 5;X ~ N(np, npq) = N $$\\left(\\frac{100}{3}, \\frac{200}{9}\\right)$$ approximately ;P(T $$\\geq$$ 40);$$\\equiv$$ P(T > 39.5) $$\\leftarrow$$ continuity correction;$$\\equiv$$ P$$\\left(Z > \\frac{39.5 - np}{\\sqrt{npq}}\\right)$$ = P $$\\left(Z > \\frac{39.5-\\frac{100}{3}}{\\sqrt{\\frac{200}{9}}} \\right)$$;= P(Z > 1.3081) = 1 - $$\\Phi$$(1.308);= 1 - 0.9045 = 0.0955(3sf)'),
('200404003031','(i) ;Let n = sample size = 50;Let $$\\mu_{0}$$ = assume $$\\mu$$ = 9.5;Let $$\\sigma^{2}$$ = Var(X) = 15;;$$\\hat{\\mu} = \\overline{x} = \\frac{\\sum x}{n} = \\frac{527.1}{50} = 10.542$$;Test $$H_{0}: \\mu = \\mu_{0}$$ against $$H_{1}: \\mu \\neq \\mu_{0}$$ a 2-tailed test for difference;At 5% significance level, critical value $$z_{0.025}$$ = 1.960;Reject $$H_{0}$$ if $$\\left| z \\right| > \\left| z_{0.025} \\right|$$;Under $$H_{0}$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \\left( \\frac{\\overline{x} - \\mu_{0}}{\\sigma / \\sqrt{n}} \\right) = \\frac{10.542 - 9.5}{\\sqrt{15/50}} = 1.902$$;;Since $$\\left| z \\right| < \\left| z_{0.025} \\right|$$, do not reject $$H_{0}$$ and conclude that, at the 5% significance level, there is insufficient evidence that $$\\mu \\neq 9.5$$;;(ii);Let $$\\mu_{1}$$ = alternative assume $$\\mu = 11.5$$;With $$\\hat{\\mu}(= 10.542) < \\mu_{1}(= 11.5)$$, in a 1-tailed test with $$H_{0}: \\mu < \\mu_{1}$$;$$\\hat{\\sigma}^{2} = \\frac{1}{n-1}\\left[\\sum x^{2} - \\frac{1}{n}\\left(\\sum x\\right)^{2}\\right]$$;= $$\\frac{1}{49}\\left[6172.31 - \\frac{1}{50}\\left(527.1\\right)^{2}\\right]$$ = 12.56;For a 1-tailed test, the $$\\alpha$$% critical value is $$z_{\\alpha}$$;Under $$H_{0}$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \\left( \\frac{\\overline{x} - \\mu_{1}}{\\sigma / \\sqrt{n}} \\right) = \\frac{10.542 - 11.5}{\\sqrt{12.56/50}} = -1.911$$;$$H_{0}$$ is accepted if $$z > - z_{\\alpha}$$;;i.e. -1.911 > -$$z_{\\alpha}$$;$$z_{\\alpha}$$ > 1.911;$$\\equiv \\Phi(z_{\\alpha}) > \\Phi(1.911)$$ ;$$\\equiv 1 - \\alpha > 0.9720$$;$$\\therefore \\alpha < 0.028$$;$$\\equiv$$ Significance level of test < 2.8%'),
