('200503003008','img;The region is bounded by the positive x-axis, the positive y-axis and the curve: ;$$Y = \\frac{1}{(x^2 + 1)^{\\frac{1}{3}}}$$;i)Using the trapezium rule, with 4 intervals of equal width of 0.25 unit, to estimate the shaded area of region R,;Trapezium rule:;$$\\int_{a}^{b} y dx \\approx \\frac{1}{2} h \\left[y_0 + y_n + 2 \\left[ y_1 + ...+ y_n - 1 \\right] \\right]$$;Where  h = width of each trapezium, and $$y_i$$ is the value of y at $$x = a + ih$$;With $$b = 1$$, $$a = 0$$ and $$n = 4$$,; $$H =  \\frac{b-a}{n} = \\frac{1-0}{4} = 0.25$$;Area of region R;= $$\\int_{0}^{1}\\frac{1}{\\left ( x^{2}+ 1 \\right )^{\\frac{1}{3}}}dx$$;= $$\\frac{1}{2} 0.25 \\left [ 1 + 0.79370 + 2\\left ( 0.97999 + 0.92832 + 0.86177 \\right )  \\right ]$$;= $$0.917(3dp)$$;(ii)Expanding $$(x^{2} + 1) ^{-\\frac{1}{3}}$$ in ascending powers of x up to, and including, the term in $$x^{4}$$,;$$\\equiv \\left ( 1 + x^{2} \\right )^{-\\frac{1}{3}};= 1 - \\frac{1}{3}x^{2} + \\frac{\\left ( -\\frac{1}{3} \\right )\\left ( -\\frac{4}{3} \\right )}{2!}\\left ( x^{2} \\right )^{2};\\approx 1 - \\frac{1}{3}x^{2} + \\frac{2}{9}x^{4}$$;Using this expansion, to get a second estimate of the area of R;= $$\\left [ x - \\frac{1}{9}x^{3} + \\frac{2}{45}x^{5} \\right ]10 ;= 0.933(3dp)$$'),
('200503003009','At the points of intersection between ;y = x - 3 and $$y^{2} + y = 2x^{2} - x + 1$$;$$\\begin{align};& \\left ( x - 3 \\right )^2 + \\left ( x -3 \\right ) = 2x^{2}- x + 1\\\\;& \\Rightarrow x^{2} - 6x + 9 + x - 3 - 2x^{2} - x +1\\\\;& x^{2} + 4x - 5  = 0\\\\;\\end{align}$$;$$\\therefore x = -5$$ or $$x = 1$$;$$\\Rightarrow y = x - 3 = -2$$ or $$-8$$;$$\\therefore$$ There are 2 points of intersection: (1,-2) and (-5,-8);$$\\begin{align};& y^{2} + y = 2x^{2} - x +1\\\\;& \\Rightarrow \\frac{d}{dx}[y^2 + y] = \\frac{d}{dx}[2x^{2} - x +1]\\\\;& 2y\\frac{dy}{dx} + \\frac{dy}{dx} = 4x -1\\\\;& (2y+1)\\frac{dy}{dx} = 4x -1\\\\;& \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{4x-1}{2y+1}\\\\;\\end{align}$$;;Gradient $$m_1$$ of line y = (1)x - 3 is 1.;Gradient $$m_2$$ of curve is given by $$\\frac{dy}{dx}$$;At (1, -2), $$m_2 = \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{4(1)-1}{2(-2)+1} = -1$$;Since $$m_2 = \\frac{1}{m_1}$$, line y = x - 3 is normal to the curve at this point.;At (-5,-8), $$m_2 = \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{4(-5)-1}{2(-8)+1} = 1.4$$;Since $$m_2 \\neq \\frac{1}{m_1}$$, line y = x - 3 is not normal to the curve at this point.;;$$\\therefore$$ The line is normal to the cruve at exactly one (1,-2) of the two points of intersection'),
('200503003010','The differential equation;$$x\\frac{d}{dx} + y = x y^{3}------(1)$$;Using the substitution; $$y^{2} = \\frac{1}{z}------(2)$$;Reducing (1):;(2) $$= y = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{z}};\\frac{d}{dx} = - \\frac{1}{2} \\frac{1}{z^{\\frac{3}{2}}}\\frac{d}{dx}------(3)$$;Substitute (3) into (1);$$X(-\\frac{1}{2}\\frac{1}{z^{\\frac{3}{2}}}\\frac{d}{dx} + \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{z}} = x \\frac{1}{z^{\\frac[3}{2}}$$;The differential equation is reduced to;$$\\frac{d}{dx} - \\frac{2z}{x} = -2$$;Solving (1):;Let $$h(x) = \\int \\frac{-2}{x}dc = -2 \\ln x = \\ln x^{-2}$$;Integrating factor:;$$\\exp h(x) = \\exp(l x ^{-2}) = x^{-2} = \\frac{1}{x^{2}}$$;General solution:; $$Z = \\exp(-h(x)) \\left [ \\int \\exp (h(x))(-2)dx \\right ];= x^\\left(2\\right)\\left [ -2\\int \\frac{1}{x^{2}}dx \\right ];=x^{2}\\left [ 2\\frac{1}{x}+ c \\right ]$$ where c is a constant;$$= 2x + cx^{2}$$;Substitute into (2);Gerneral solution of differential equation; $$Y^{2} = \\frac{1}{2x+cx^{2}}$$ where c is a constant'),
('200503003011','(i);$$\\begin{align};&ff(\\lambda) =  f[(\\lambda)^{2} - 6\\lambda(\\lambda)] \\\\;&= f(-5\\lambda^{2})\\\\;&=(-5\\lambda^{2})^{2} - 6\\lambda(-5\\lambda^{2})\\\\;&=25\\lambda^{4} + 30\\lambda^{3}\\\\;\\end{align}$$;;(ii);img;$$f(x) = x^{2} - 6\\lambda x = ( x - 3 \\lambda)^2 - 9\\lambda^{2}$$ ;Since $$(x - 3\\lambda)^{2} \\geq 0, f(x) = (x-3\\lambda)^{2} - 9\\lambda^{2} \\geq -9\\lambda^{2}$$;i.e. $$D_f$$ is $$f(x) \\geq -9\\lambda^{2}$$;Function f does not have an inverse beacuse it is not a one-one function.;$$f(x) \\equiv (x-3\\lambda)^{2} - 9\\lambda^2$$;$$\\Rightarrow f(3\\lambda + x) = f(3\\lambda -x)$$;i.e. $$f(x)$$ is symmetrical about $$x = 3\\lambda$$;$$\\Rightarrow f(x)$$ could be a one-one function if its domain is restricted to one side of $$x = 3\\lambda$$;$$\\therefore k = 3\\lambda$$;;Let $$y = f^{-1}(x)$$;$$\\Rightarrow f(y) = x$$;i.e. ;$$\\begin{align} &y^{2} - 6\\lambda y = x\\\\;&y^{2} - 6\\lambda y - x = 0\\\\;&\\therefore y = \\frac{-(-6\\lambda) \\pm \\sqrt{(-6\\lambda)^{2} - 4(1)(-x)}}{2(1)}\\\\;&= 3\\lambda \\pm \\sqrt{9\\lambda^{2} + x};\\end{align}$$;$$\\therefore$$ For $$x \\geq 3\\lambda$$,;$$f^{-1}(x) = 3\\lambda + \\sqrt{9\\lambda^{2} +x} $$;For $$x \\leq 3\\lambda$$,;$$f^{-1}(x) = 3\\lambda - \\sqrt{9\\lambda^{2} +x} $$'),
('200503003012','With $$t = \\tan{\\theta}$$,;$$\\begin{align};& \\tan 3 {\\theta} = \\tan {(2\\theta + \\theta}) \\\\;& = \\frac{\\tan{2\\theta} + \\tan{\\theta}}{1 - \\tan{2\\theta\\tan{\\theta}}}\\\\;& = \\frac{\\frac{2t}{1-t^{2}}+t}{1-\\frac{2t}{1-t^{2}}t}\\\\ ;& =\\frac{2t+t(1-t^{2})}{(1-t^{2}) - 2t^{2}}\\\\;& = \\frac{3t-t^{3}}{1-3t^{2}}\\\\;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};& 4t^3 + 3t^{2} - 12t - 1 = 0\\\\;& \\Rightarrow 4t^{3} - 12t = 1-3t^{2}\\\\;& -4(3t-t^{3}) = 1-3t^{2}\\\\;& \\frac{3t-t^{3}}{1-3t^{2}} = \\frac{1}{4}\\\\;& \\equiv \\tan{3\\theta} = \\frac{1}{4}, where t = \\tan{\\theta}\\\\;& 3\\theta = 180n^{\\circ} - 14.04^{\\circ}, n \\in \\mathbb{Z} \\\\;& \\theta = 60n^{\\circ} - 4.68^{\\circ}\\\\;\\end{align}$$;Since equation in $$t(=\\tan{\\theta})$$ is cubic,;$$\\theta = -4.68^{\\circ}, 55.32^{\\circ},$$ or $$115.32^{\\circ}$$;$$\\therefore t = \\tan{(-4.68^{\\circ})}, \\tan{(55.32^{\\circ})},$$ or $$\\tan{(115.32^{\\circ})}$$;$$= -0.08186, 1.4453, -2.114$$;$$= -0.0818, 1.45, -2.11 (3sf)$$'),
