('200504003026','Let X = height of a person;Let $$\\mu$$ =E(X);Let $$\\sigma^2$$ =Var(X);$$\\begin{align} ;& X \\sim N ( \\mu , \\sigma^2 ) \\\\;& P(X > 1.50) = 0.75 \\\\;& \\Rightarrow P ( Z > \\frac{1.50 - \\mu}{\\sigma} ) = 0.75 \\\\;& \\equiv P(Z < \\frac{\\mu - 1.50}{\\sigma}) = 0.75 \\\\;& \\equiv \\Phi ( \\frac{\\mu - 1.50}{\\sigma} ) = 0.75 \\\\;& \\frac{\\mu - 1.50}{\\sigma}= \\Phi^{- 1}(0.75) = 0.674 \\\\;& \\mu - 1.50 = 0.674\\sigma &----(1)\\\\;;&P ( X > 1.90 ) = 0.10 \\\\;& \\Rightarrow P(Z > \\frac{1.90 - \\mu}{\\sigma}) = 0.10 \\\\;& \\equiv P ( Z < \\frac{1.90 - \\mu}{\\sigma} ) = 1 - 0.10 = 0.90 \\\\;& \\equiv \\Phi(\\frac{1.90 - \\mu}{\\sigma}) = 0.90 \\\\;& \\frac{1.90 - \\mu}{\\sigma} = \\Phi^{- 1} ( 0.90 ) = 1.282 \\\\;& 1.90 - \\mu = 1.282 \\sigma &----(2)\\\\;\\end{align}$$;;Eqn(1)+Eqn(2):;$$ 0.40 = 1.956 \\sigma \\Rightarrow \\sigma = 0.2045 $$;Subst $$ \\sigma = 0.2045 $$ into eqn(1):;$$ \\mu - 1.50 = 0.674(0.2045) $$;$$ \\Rightarrow \\mu = 1.6378 $$;$$\\begin{align}  ;\\\\ P ( X > 1.81 ) ;\\\\ \\equiv P(Z > \\frac{1.81 - \\mu}{\\sigma}) ;\\\\ = P(Z > \\frac{1.81 - 1.6378}{0.2045}) ;\\\\ = P ( Z > 0.8421 ) ;\\\\ \\equiv 1 - \\Phi ( 0.842 ) ;\\\\ = 1 - 0.8000 = 0.200(3sf);\\end{align}$$;;Let n =sample size = 80;$$ X \\sim N ( \\mu , \\sigma^2 ) \\Rightarrow \\overline{X} \\sim N ( \\mu , \\sigma^2 / n ) $$;$$\\begin{align}  ;\\\\ P(\\overline{X}> 1.69) ;\\\\ \\equiv P ( Z > \\frac{1.60 - \\mu}{\\sigma / \\sqrt{n}} ) ;\\\\ = P ( Z > \\frac{1.60 - 1.6378}{0.2045 / \\sqrt{80}} ) ;\\\\ = P(Z > 2.2831) ;\\\\ \\equiv 1 - \\Phi(2.283) ;\\\\ = 1 - 0.9888 ;\\\\= 0.0112 = 0.011 (3dp);\\end{align}$$'),
('200504003027','For a uniform (rectangular) distribution with $$ l - 0.03 \\leq x \\leq l + 0.03$$,;$$\\begin{align} ;&f(x) &= 1/0.06, &l - 0.03 \\leq x \\leq l+0.03\\\\;& &=0, & otherwise\\\\; \\end{align}$$;;Let $$\\mu$$=E(X);Let $$\\sigma^2$$=Var(X);Deduce that f(x) is symmetrical about $$x = l$$ ;$$\\mu = E ( X ) = l $$;$$\\begin{align}  ;{\\sigma^2 = \\int}^\\infty_{- \\infty}(x- \\mu)^2. f(x)dx ;\\\\ {\\equiv \\int}^{l + 0.03}_{l-0.03}(x-l)^2.(1/0.06) dx ;\\\\ = {\\left[ \\frac{1}{3}(x-l)^3(1/0.06) \\right]}^{l + 0.03}_{l-0.03};\\\\ = ( 1 / 0.18 ) [ ( 0.03 )^3 - ( - 0.03 )^3 ] ;\\\\ = 0.0003;\\end{align}$$;;$$T = \\sum^{50}_{r = 1} X$$;$$E ( T ) = E ( \\sum^{50}_{r = 1} X ) = 50E ( X ) = 50l $$;$$Var ( T ) = Var ( \\sum^{50}_{r = 1} X ) = 50Var ( X )$$;$$= 50 ( 0.0003 ) = 0.015$$;Since sample size (=50) is large, Central Limit Theorem;T ~ N(50l,0.015) approximately;;Deduce that 5 observations of T is equal to (5 x 50 =) 250 observations of X;Let n = sample size = 250;$$\\begin{align} \\hat{l} \\equiv \\hat{\\mu} = \\overline{x} = \\frac{\\Sigma t}{n} = \\frac{499.53}{250} = 1.99812\\end{align}$$;Let $$l_0$$ = assumed $$l$$ (or $$\\mu$$) =2;Test $$H_0: l = l_0$$ against $$H_1: l < l_0$$ a 1-tailed test for less;The 1% critical value, $$z_{0.01} = 2.326$$;Reject $$H_0$$ if $$z < -z_{0.01}$$;Under $$H_0$$, the test statistic is ;$$\\begin{align} z = \\frac{\\overline{x} - l_0}{\\sigma / \\sqrt{n}} = \\frac{1.99812 - 2}{\\sqrt{0.0003 / 250}} = - 1.7162 \\end{align}$$;Since $$z > -z_{0.01}$$, do not reject $$H_0$$ and conclude that, at the 1% level of significance, there is insufficient evidence that $$l$$<2.'),
