('200604003027','X~U(0,1) or R(0,1);i.e. X has the density function ;$$\\begin{align}  ;& f(x) &= 1 &0 < x < 1  ;\\\\&  &= 0 &otherwise. ;\\end{align}$$;;Let $$\\mu = E ( X ) = \\frac{1}{2} ( 0 + 1 ) = \\frac{1}{2} $$;$$\\begin{align} ;Var(X) =   \\int^{\\infty}_{- \\infty}(x- \\mu)^2 \\cdot f(x) dx ;\\\\ =   \\int^1_0(x- \\frac{1}{2})^2 \\cdot(1) dx ;\\\\ = {\\left[ \\frac{1}{3}\\left(x- \\frac{1}{2}\\right)^3 \\right]}^1_0 ;\\\\ = \\frac{1}{3} \\left[ \\left( \\frac{1}{2} \\right)^3 - \\left( - \\frac{1}{2} \\right)^3 \\right] = \\frac{1}{12}; \\end{align}$$;;$$Y\\sim U(-1,2)$$ and $$Y \\equiv 3X - 1$$;$$\\begin{align}  \\;E ( Y ) \\equiv E ( 3X - 1 ) ;\\\\ = 3E(X) - 1 ;\\\\ = 3 \\left( \\frac{1}{2} \\right) - 1 = \\frac{1}{2} ;\\end{align}$$;$$\\begin{align};\\\\ Var ( Y ) \\equiv Var ( 3X - 1 ) ;\\\\ = 3^2 Var(X) +0 ;\\\\ = 9 \\left( \\frac{1}{12} \\right) = \\frac{3}{4};\\end{align}$$;;;$$ T = \\lambda X + ( 1 - \\lambda ) Y $$;$$\\begin{align}  ;\\\\ \\Rightarrow E(T) = E [ \\lambda X +(1 - \\lambda) Y ] ;\\\\ = \\lambda E ( X ) +( 1 - \\lambda ) E ( Y ) ;\\\\ = \\lambda\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right) + (1 - \\lambda)\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right) ;\\end{align}$$;$$  = \\frac{1}{2} \\leftarrow$$ independent of $$\\lambda$$;;$$\\begin{align}  ;Var ( T ) = Var [ \\lambda X +( 1 - \\lambda ) Y ] ;\\\\ = \\lambda^2 Var  (X) +(1 - \\lambda)^2 Var(Y) ;\\\\ = \\frac{1}{12} \\lambda^2 +\\frac{3}{4} ( 1 - \\lambda )^2 ;\\\\ = \\frac{1}{12}[ \\lambda^2 +9(1 - 2 \\lambda +\\lambda^2)]  ;\\\\ = \\frac{1}{12} [ 10 \\lambda^2 - 18\\lambda +9 ] ;\\\\ = \\frac{10}{12}\\left[ \\lambda^2 - \\frac{18}{10}\\lambda +\\frac{9}{10}\\right] ;\\\\ = \\frac{5}{6} \\left[ \\left( \\lambda - \\frac{9}{10} \\right)^2 - \\left( \\frac{9}{10} \\right)^2 +\\frac{9}{10} \\right];\\end{align}$$;;Deduce that Var(T) is smallest when ;$$\\begin{align} \\lambda-\\frac{9}{10} = 0,\\end{align}$$  $$\\begin{align}i.e. \\lambda = \\frac{9}{10} \\end{align}$$'),
('200604003028','Let X= speed of a car;Let $$\\mu=E(X)$$;Let $$\\sigma^2=Var(X)$$;;$$\\begin{align};X \\sim N ( \\mu , \\sigma^2 ) ;\\\\ P(X > 125) = 1/80 = 0.0125 ;\\\\ \\equiv P ( Z > \\frac{125 - \\mu}{\\sigma} ) = 0.0125 ;\\\\ \\equiv P\\left(Z < \\frac{125 - \\mu}{\\sigma}\\right) = 1 - 0.0125 = 0.9875 ;\\\\ \\Phi ( \\frac{125 - \\mu}{\\sigma} ) = 0.9875 ;\\\\ \\frac{125 - \\mu}{\\sigma}= \\Phi^{- 1}(0.9875) = 2.240 ;\\\\ \\mu +2.240\\sigma = 125 ----(1); \\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align} ;P ( X < 40 ) = 1 / 10 = 0.1 ;\\\\ \\equiv P(Z < \\frac{40 - \\mu}{\\sigma}) = 0.1 ;\\\\ \\equiv P ( Z < \\frac{\\mu - 40}{\\sigma} ) = 1 - 0.1 = 0.9 ;\\\\ \\Phi(\\frac{\\mu - 40}{\\sigma}) = 0.9 ;\\\\ \\frac{\\mu - 40}{\\sigma} = \\Phi^{- 1} ( 0.9 ) = 1.282 ;\\\\ \\mu - 1.282 \\sigma = 40 ----(2); \\end{align}$$;;Eqn(1) - (2):;$$ 3.522\\sigma = 85$$;$$ \\Rightarrow \\sigma =24.134 = 24.1 km h^{-1} (3sf)$$;Subst $$\\sigma = 24.134$$ into eqn(2):;$$ \\mu - 1.282(24.134) = 40 $$;$$ \\Rightarrow \\mu =70.94 = 70.9 km h^{-1}$$;;(i) Let n = no. of cars in sample = 10;Let p = P(X<40) = 0.1 and q = 1- p = 0.9;Let Y = no. of cars out of n with X < 40;;Y ~ B(n,p);P(at least 7 cars with X > 40);$$\\equiv$$ P(at most 3 cars with X < 40);$$=P ( Y \\leq 3 ) $$;$$= P(Y = 0) +P(Y = 1) +P(Y = 2) +P(Y = 3) $$;$$= q^n +^n{C_1} p^1 q^{n - 1} +^n{C_2} p^2 q^{n - 2} +^n{C_3} p^3 q^{n - 3} $$;$$=(0.9)^{10}+ ^{10}{C_1}{(0.1)}^1 {(0.9)}^9 + ^{10}{C_2} {( 0.1 )}^2 {( 0.9 )}^8 + ^{10}{C_3} {( 0.1 )}^3 {( 0.9 )}^7 $$;$$ = 0.9872 = 0.987(3sf)$$;;(ii) Let m = no. of cars in $$2^{nd}$$ sample = 100;Let S= no. of cars out of m with X < 40;;S ~ B(m, p);Since m(=100) is large, mp = (100)(0.1) = 10 >5 and mq = (100)(0.9) = 90 >5,;S~N(mp,npq) approximately;P(at most 8 cars with X < 40);= P(S $$\\leq$$8);$$\\equiv$$ P(S<8.5)$$\\leftarrow$$ continuity correction;$$\\begin{align} \\equiv P\\left(Z < \\frac{8.5-mp}{\\sqrt{mpq}}\\right);\\\\ = P\\left(Z < \\frac{8.5-100(0.1)}{\\sqrt{100(0.1)(0.9)}}\\right);\\\\ = P(Z < -0.5000);\\\\ = 1 - \\Phi(0.5000);\\\\ = 1 - 0.6915 ;\\\\ = 0.3085 = 0.309(3sf)\\end{align}$$'),
('200604003029','It meant that there is a 95% confidence level that the interval (3.52, 414) encloses the true value of $$\\mu$$.;It is not necessary to make any assumptions because the Central Limit Theorem suggests that the sample mean of a large sample is approximately normally distributed.;;Let X = time per week a teenager spend playing computer games;Let $$\\sigma^{2}$$ = Var(X);(3.52,4.14) is a 95% confidence interval;$$\\begin{align}  \\Rightarrow (3.52, 4.14) = \\left[\\overline{x} - z_{0.025} \\frac{\\hat{\\sigma}}{\\sqrt{n}}, \\overline{x} + z_{0.025} \\frac{\\hat{\\sigma}}{\\sqrt{n}}\\right];\\\\ \\Rightarrow \\overline{x} = \\frac{1}{2} (3.52+4.14) = 3.83;\\\\ z_{0.025} \\frac{\\hat{\\sigma}}{\\sqrt{n}} = \\frac{1}{2}(4.14-3.52) = 0.31;\\\\ \\therefore  \\frac{\\hat{\\sigma}}{\\sqrt{n}} = 0.31/z_{0.025} = 0.31/1.960 = 0.15816;\\\\ z_{0.025} \\frac{\\hat{\\sigma}}{\\sqrt{n}} = (2.576)(0.15816) = 0.4074\\end{align}$$;A symmetric 99% confidence interval for $$\\mu$$;$$\\begin{align}  = \\left[\\overline{x} - z_{0.005} \\frac{\\hat{\\sigma}}{\\sqrt{n}}, \\overline{x} + z_{0.005} \\frac{\\hat{\\sigma}}{\\sqrt{n}}\\right];\\\\ = [3.83-0.407, 3.83+0.407];\\\\ = [3.423, 4.237] = [3.42,4.24](3sf)\\end{align}$$;;(i) Since $${I_1}^\'$$ encloses $$I_1$$,;P(both $$I_1$$ and $${I_1}^\'$$ to contain $$\\mu$$);= P($$I_1$$ contains $$\\mu$$) = 95%;;(ii) Since $${I_1}^\'$$ encloses $$I_1$$,;P(exactly one of $$I_1$$ and $${I_1}^\'$$ to contain $$\\mu$$);= P($${I_1}^\'$$ contains $$\\mu$$) - P($$I_1$$ contains $$\\mu$$);=0.99 - 0.95 = 0.04 $$\\equiv$$ 4%;;(iii) P(both $$I_1$$ and $$I_2$$ to contain $$\\mu$$);= P($$I_1$$ contains $$\\mu$$) $$\\cdot$$ P($$I_2$$ contains $$\\mu$$);=(0.95)(0.95) = 0.9025 $$\\equiv$$ 90.25%;;(iv) P(exactly one of $$I_1$$ and $$I_2$$ to contain $$\\mu$$);= P($$I_1$$ contains $$\\mu$$) $$\\cdot$$ P($$I_2$$ doesn\'t contains $$\\mu$$) + P($$I_1$$ doesn\'t contains $$\\mu$$) $$\\cdot$$ P($$I_2$$ contains $$\\mu$$);= (0.95)(1-0.95)+(1-0.95)(0.95);= 0.095 $$\\equiv$$ 9.5%'),
('200604003030','$$\\begin{align} X = 0.4U + 0.6V;\\\\ \\Rightarrow P(x < X < x+\\delta x) ;\\\\ = \\int^{x+\\delta x}_{x} \\{0.4g(t) + 0.6h(t)\\} dt;\\\\ = \\{0.4g(x) +0.6h(x)\\} \\delta x for small \\delta x\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align} f(x) &= \\lim_{\\delta x \\to \\infty} \\frac{P(x < X < x+\\delta x) }{\\delta x}&\\\\ ;&=  \\lim_{\\delta x \\to \\infty} \\frac{\\{0.4g(x) +0.6h(x)\\} \\delta x }{\\delta x}&\\\\;&= 0.4g(x) + 0.6h(x) &\\\\;&= \\frac{4}{10}\\left[\\frac{1}{6}(2x+1)\\right] + \\frac{6}{10}\\left[\\frac{1}{2}(2-x)\\right] &for 0< x < 2 \\\\ ;&= \\frac{2}{15}x + \\frac{1}{15} + \\frac{3}{5} - \\frac{3}{10}x &\\\\;&=\\frac{2}{3} - \\frac{1}{6} x = \\frac{1}{6}(4-x)\\end{align}$$;;Distribution function of X, ;$$\\begin{align} F(x) &= \\int^{x}_{-\\infty} f(t)dt &\\\\;&= \\int^{x}_{0} (4-t)dt & for 0< x < 2\\\\ ;&= \\frac{1}{6}\\left[4t - \\frac{1}{2}t^2\\right]^{x}_{0}&\\\\;&=\\frac{1}{6}\\left[4x-\\frac{1}{2}x^2\\right] = \\frac{1}{12}x(8-x)\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align} \\therefore F(X) = &0 & x < 0 \\\\;&\\frac{1}{12}x(8-x) & 0\\leq x\\leq 2 \\\\;&1 &x > 2\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align} E(X^2) &= \\int^{\\infty}_{-\\infty} x^2 \\cdot f(x) dx &\\\\;&= \\int^{2}_{0} x^2 \\cdot \\frac{1}{6}(4-x) dx & for 0 < x < 2\\\\;&= \\frac{1}{6} \\int^{2}_{0}(4x^2-x^3)dx&\\\\;&= \\frac{1}{6} \\left[\\frac{4}{3}x^3 - \\frac{1}{4}x^4\\right]^2_0&\\\\;&=\\frac{1}{6}\\left[\\frac{4}{3}(2)^3 - \\frac{1}{4}(2)^4 \\right]=\\frac{10}{9}&\\\\ \\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align} E(X^4) &= \\int^{\\infty}_{-\\infty} x^4 \\cdot f(x) dx &\\\\;&= \\int^{2}_{0} x^4 \\cdot \\frac{1}{6}(4-x) dx & for 0 < x < 2\\\\;&= \\frac{1}{6} \\int^{2}_{0}(4x^4-x^5)dx&\\\\;&= \\frac{1}{6} \\left[\\frac{4}{5}x^5 - \\frac{1}{6}x^6\\right]^2_0&\\\\;&=\\frac{1}{6}\\left[\\frac{4}{5}(2)^5 - \\frac{1}{6}(2)^6 \\right]=\\frac{112}{45}&\\\\ \\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align} Var(X^2) &= E(X^4) - [E(X^2)]^2\\\\;&=\\frac{112}{45} - \\left[\\frac{10}{9}\\right]^2 \\\\;&= 1.254 = 1.25(3sf)\\end{align}$$'),
('200703003001','Given an equation such that ;$$\\begin{align} ;\\\\ \\frac{2x^2-\\ x-19}{x^2+\\ 3x+2}-\\ 1 = \\frac{\\left(2x^2-\\ x-19\\right)-\\ (\\ x^2+\\ 3x+2)}{x^2+\\ 3x+2}  & ---- (1); \\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ To prove the relation:;$$\\begin{align}  ;LHS of (1)  &= \\frac{2x^2 - x - 19 -(x^2+3x+2)}{x^2+3x+2};\\\\ &= \\frac{2x^2 - x - 19 -x^2-3x-2}{x^2+3x+2};\\\\ &= \\frac{x^2-\\ 4x-21}{x^2+\\ 3x+2} ;\\\\ &= RHS of (1) ;\\end{align}$$;;Hence, without using calculator,;$$\\therefore$$ Solving the inequality:;$$\\begin{align} ;\\\\ \\frac{2x^2-\\ x-19}{x^2+\\ 3x+2}\\ >1 ;\\\\ \\frac{2x^2-\\ x-19}{x^2+\\ 3x+2}\\ -1 >0 & ----(2);  \\end{align}$$;;Substitute (1) into (2):;$$\\begin{align};\\\\ \\frac{x^2-\\ 4x-21}{x^2+\\ 3x+2}\\ >0 \\Rightarrow \\frac{\\left(\\ x-7\\right)(x+3)}{\\left(x+1\\right)(x+2)}\\ >0 ;\\\\ \\Rightarrow \\left(x-7\\right)\\left(x+3\\right)\\left(x+1\\right)(x+2) >\\ 0; \\end{align}$$;;Critical values are -3, -2 and -1 and 7;img;$$\\therefore$$ Solution set of the inequality:;x<-3 or -2 < x < -1 or x > 7'),
