('200703003010','(i) $$\\therefore$$ To show that $$3r^2 - 5r +2 = 0 ----(1)$$;$$1^{st}$$ term of geometric series = first term of the arithmetic series  = $$a$$;$$2^{nd}$$ term of geometric series = $$4^{th}$$ term of arithmetic series;;$$\\begin{align} \\Rightarrow ar = a + 3d \\Rightarrow ar - a = 3d;\\\\ \\Rightarrow a(r-1) = 3d \\Rightarrow a = \\frac{3d}{r-1} ----(2) \\end{align}$$;;$$3^{rd}$$ term fo geometric series  = $$6^{th}$$ term of the arithmetic series;$$\\Rightarrow ar^2 = a + 5d ----(3)$$;;Substitute (2) into (3):;$$\\begin{align} \\left( \\frac{3d}{r-1}\\right)(r^2) = \\frac{3d}{r-1}+5d ;\\\\ (d)\\left(\\frac{3r^2}{r-1}\\right) = (d)\\left(\\frac{3}{r-1}+5\\right);\\\\ \\frac{3r^2}{r-1} = \\frac{3+5(r-1)}{r-1};\\\\ 3r^2 = 3+5r-5 \\Rightarrow 3r^2 = 5r -2\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The relation is $$3r^2-5r +2 = 0$$;;(ii) ;$$\\therefore$$ To show that geometric series is convergent:;Solving (1):;$$ (3r-2)(r-1)=0 $$;$$ r = \\frac{2}{3} ----(4)$$  or $$r=1$$ (Rejected, since r is a ratio of a geometric series. therefore $$r\\neq)1$$;$$\\therefore$$ Since $$r=\\frac{2}{3} < 1$$, the geometric series is convergent.;$$\\therefore$$ Sum to infinity, in term of $$\\alpha$$,;$$\\begin{align} S_{\\infty} = \\frac{a}{1-r} = \\frac{a}{1-\\left(\\frac{2}{3}\\right)} = 3a \\end{align}$$;;(iii);Given that S denotes the sum of the first n terms of the arithmetic series where the first term, a > 0.;For S to exceed 4a,;$$\\therefore$$ Let {Z} be the set of possible values of n.;Substitute (4) into (2):;$$\\begin{align} a = \\frac{3d}{\\left(\\frac{2}{3}\\right)-1} \\Rightarrow 3d = \\frac{2}{3}a -a \\Rightarrow 3d =-\\frac{1}{3}a;\\\\ \\Rightarrow d=-\\frac{1}{9}a ----(5)\\end{align}$$;;Sum of the first n terms of the arithmetic series,;$$\\begin{align} S = \\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)[2a+(n-1)d] \\end{align}$$;;Deduce, ;$$\\begin{align} \\{Z\\} \\equiv \\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)[2a+(n-1)d] > 4a ;\\\\ \\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)\\left[2a+(n-1)\\left(-\\frac{1}{9}a\\right)\\right] > 4a;\\\\ \\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)(a)\\left[2+(n-1)\\left(-\\frac{1}{9}\\right)\\right] > 4a \\end{align}$$;;Since $$\\alpha > 0$$, therefore, ;$$\\begin{align} \\Rightarrow \\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)\\left[2+(n-1)\\left(-\\frac{1}{9}\\right)\\right] > 4;\\\\ \\Rightarrow \\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)\\left(2-\\frac{1}{9}n+\\frac{1}{9}\\right) > 4 ;\\\\ \\Rightarrow \\left(\\frac{n}{2}\\right)\\left(2\\frac{1}{9}-\\frac{1}{9}n\\right) - 4 > 0 ;\\\\ \\Rightarrow \\frac{19n}{18} - \\frac{n^2}{18} - 4 > 0\\end{align}$$;;From GC, roots of the equation:;The critical values are n = 5.227 or n =13.77;Since n is an integer,;$$\\therefore$$ The set of possible values for n for which S exeeds 4a is $$\\{n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^{+}, 6 \\leq n \\leq 13\\}$$'),
('200703003011','For $$0 \\leq t \\leq \\frac{1}{2}\\pi$$, a curve is defined by a pair of parametric equations:;$$ x = \\cos^{2}{t} ----(1)$$;$$ y = \\sin^{3}{t} ----(2)$$;(i);Sketch;img;;(ii);With respect to the origin O, the trangent to the curve at $$(cos^{2}{\\theta}, \\sin^{2}{\\theta}) $$ meets the x- and y-axes at Q and R respectively. It is given that $$0 < \\theta < \\frac{1}{2}\\pi$$;;$$\\therefore$$ To deduce the area of triangle OQR:;Differentiating (1) wrt x, ;$$\\begin{align} \\frac{dx}{dt} = 2(\\cos{t})(-\\sin{t}) = -2\\sin{t}\\cos{t} \\end{align}$$;Differentiating (2) wrt x,;$$\\begin{align} \\frac{dy}{dt} = 3(\\sin^{2}{t})(\\cos{t}) = 3\\sin^{2}{t}\\cos{t} \\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align} \\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{dy}{dt} / \\frac{dx}{dt} = \\frac{3\\sin^{2}{t}\\cos{t}}{-2\\sin{t}\\cos{t}} = -\\frac{3}{2}\\sin{t}\\end{align}$$;;At the point $$(\\cos^{2}{\\theta}, \\sin^{3}{\\theta})$$, t  = $$\\theta \\Rightarrow \\frac{dy}{dx} = -\\frac{3}{2}\\sin{\\theta}$$;;Equation of the tangent at $$(\\cos^{2}{\\theta}, \\sin^{3}{\\theta})$$:;$$\\begin{align} y_1-y_2 = m(x_1-x_2);\\\\ y-\\sin^{3}{\\theta} = - \\frac{3}{2}\\sin{\\theta}(x-\\cos^{2}{\\theta});\\\\ y=-\\frac{3}{2}\\sin{\\theta}(x-\\cos^{2}\\theta)+\\sin^{3}{\\theta}\\end{align}$$;;At x = 0, $$\\begin{align} y = \\frac{3}{2}\\sin{\\theta}\\cos^{2}{\\theta} +\\sin^{3}{\\theta} \\end{align}$$;At y = 0, $$\\begin{align} -\\frac{3}{2}\\sin{\\theta}(x-\\cos^{2}\\theta)+\\sin^{3}{\\theta} = 0 \\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align} -\\frac{3}{2} x \\sin{\\theta} + \\frac{3}{2}\\sin{\\theta}\\cos^{2}{\\theta} + \\sin^{3}{\\theta} = 0;\\\\ \\frac{3}{2}x\\sin{\\theta} = \\frac{3}{2}\\sin{\\theta}\\cos^{2}{\\theta}+\\sin^{3}{\\theta} ;\\\\ x = \\cos^{2}{\\theta} + \\frac{2}{3}\\sin^{2}{\\theta}\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The area of triangle OQR:;$$\\begin{align} = \\frac{1}{2}\\left(\\cos^{2}{\\theta} + \\frac{2}{3}\\sin^2{\\theta}\\right)\\left(\\frac{3}{2}\\sin{\\theta}\\cos^{2}{\\theta}+\\sin^{3}{\\theta}\\right) ;\\\\ = \\frac{1}{2}\\left(\\frac{3}{2}\\sin{\\theta}\\cos^{4}{\\theta} + \\cos^{2}{\\theta}\\sin^{3}\\theta+\\cos^{2}{\\theta}\\sin^{3}{\\theta}+\\frac{2}{3}\\sin^{5}{\\theta}\\right);\\\\ = \\frac{3}{4}\\sin{\\theta}\\cos^{4}{\\theta} + \\cos^{2}{\\theta}\\sin^{3}{\\theta}+\\frac{1}{3}\\sin^{5}{\\theta};\\\\ = \\frac{1}{12}\\sin{\\theta}(9\\cos^{4}{\\theta} + 12\\cos^{2}{\\theta}\\sin^{2}{\\theta}+4\\sin^{4}{\\theta});\\\\ = \\frac{1}{12}\\sin{\\theta}(3\\cos^{2}{\\theta} + 2\\sin^{2}{\\theta})^2\\end{align}$$;;(iii);For $$0 \\leq t \\leq \\frac{1}{2}\\pi$$,;$$\\therefore$$ To show that the area under the curve is $$2\\int^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} \\cos{t}\\sin^{4}{t} \\space dt$$;;Considering (1):;When x = 0, $$\\cos{t} = 0 \\Rightarrow t = \\frac{\\pi}{2}$$;When x = 1, $$\\cos{t} = 1 \\Rightarrow t = 0$$;;Differentiating (1) wrt t:;$$\\begin{align} \\frac{dx}{dt} = 2\\cos{t}(-\\sin{t});\\\\ \\Rightarrow dx = 2\\cos{t}(-\\sin{t}) \\space dt  ----(3)\\end{align}$$;;Area under curve  = $$\\int^{1}_{0} y \\space dx ----(4)$$;Substitute (3) into (4):;$$\\therefore$$ The area under curve;$$\\begin{align} = \\int^{0}_{-\\frac{\\pi}{2}} (\\sin^{3}{t}[2\\cos{t}(-\\sin{t}) \\space dt] ;\\\\ = 2 \\int^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} \\cos{t}\\sin^{4}{t} \\space dt ----(5)\\end{align}$$;$$\\therefore$$ Using the substitution $$\\sin{t} = u ----(6)$$;;Differentiating (5) wrt u:;$$\\begin{align} \\cos{t}\\frac{dt}{du} = 1 \\Rightarrow dt = \\frac{du}{\\cos{t}} ----(7) \\end{align}$$;;At $$t = 0, u = \\sin{(0)} = 0$$;At $$t=\\frac{1}{2}\\pi, u = \\sin{(\\frac{1}{2}\\pi)} = 1 $$;;Substitute (7) into (5):;$$\\therefore$$ Area under curve;$$\\begin{align} = 2\\int^{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}_{0} \\cos{t}\\sin^{4}{t} \\space dt;\\\\ = 2 \\int^{1}_{0} (\\cos{t})(u^4)\\left(\\frac{du}{\\cos{t}}\\right) ;\\\\ = 2 \\int^{1}_{0} u^4 \\space du ;\\\\ = 2\\left[\\frac{u^5}{5}\\right]^{1}_{0};\\\\ = 2\\left(\\frac{1}{5}\\right) - 0 ;\\\\ = \\frac{2}{5} \\space units^{2}\\end{align}$$'),
('200704003001','$$\\therefore$$ Let $$T_L$$ be the total amount paid by Lee Lian. ;Let P, M and L represent price per kilogram of pineapples, mangoes and lychees respectively;;1.15P + 0.60M + 0.55L = 8.28;1.20P + 0.45M + 0.30L = 6.84;2015P + 0.90M  + 0.65L = 13.05;;$$\\begin{align} \\begin{pmatrix}1.15&0.60&0.55\\\\1.20&0.45&0.30\\\\2.15&0.90&0.65\\end{pmatrix}\\begin{pmatrix}P\\\\M\\\\L\\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix}8.28\\\\6.84\\\\13.05\\end{pmatrix} ;\\\\ \\begin{pmatrix}P\\\\M\\\\L\\end{pmatrix}  = \\begin{pmatrix}1.15&0.60&0.55\\\\1.20&0.45&0.30\\\\2.15&0.90&0.65\\end{pmatrix}^{-1}\\begin{pmatrix}8.28\\\\6.84\\\\13.05\\end{pmatrix} ;\\\\ = \\begin{pmatrix}3.50\\\\2.60\\\\4.90\\end{pmatrix} \\space (From \\space GC) \\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The total amount that person Lee Lian paid for the fruits, ;$$T_L$$ ;= 1.30P + 0.25M + 0.50L;= 1.30(3.50) + 0.25(2.60) + 0.50(4.90);= $7.65'),
('200704003002','(i) ;Let $$P_n$$ be $$u_n = \\frac{1}{n^2}$$ where $$ n \\in \\mathbb{Z}^{+}$$;When n = 1, ;$$P_1 = U_1$$;LHS of $$P_1 = 1$$;RHS OF $$P_1 = \\frac{1}{1^2} = 1 =$$ LHS of $$P_1$$;$$\\therefore P_1$$ is true.;;Assume $$P_k$$ is true for some $$k \\in \\mathbb{Z}^{+}, k \\leq n$$: $$u_k=\\frac{1}{k^2}$$;When n=k+1,;RHS of $$\\begin{align} P_{k+1} = \\frac{1}{(k+1)^2}  \\end{align}$$;LHS of $$\\begin{align} u_{k+1} = u_{k} - \\frac{2k+1}{k^2(k+1)^2} \\end{align}$$;$$\\begin{align} =\\frac{1}{k^2} - \\frac{2k+1}{k^2(k+1)^2} = \\frac{(k+1)^2 - (2k+1)}{k^2(k+1)^2} ;\\\\ = \\frac{k^2 + 2k +1 -2k -1}{k^2(k+1)^2} = \\frac{k^2}{k^2(k+1)^2};\\\\ = \\frac{1}{(k+1)^2} = RHS \\space of \\space P_{k+1}\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore P_{k+1}$$ is true when $$P_k$$ is true.;$$\\therefore$$ By mathematical induction, $$P_n$$ is true for all $$ n\\in \\mathbb{Z}^{+}$$;;(ii) ;$$\\begin{align} \\sum^{N}_{n=1} \\frac{2n+1}{n^2(n+1)^2};\\\\ = \\sum^{N}_{n=1} (u_n - u_{n+1});\\\\  = u_1 - u_2 + u_2 - u_3 +...+u_{N-1} - u_N + u_N - U_{N+1};\\\\ = u_1-u_{N+1} \\space (Method \\space of \\space differences) ;\\\\ = 1- \\frac{1}{(N+1)^2}\\end{align}$$;;(iii);$$\\therefore$$ The reason that the series in [art(ii) is convergent is as ;$$\\begin{align} N \\rightarrow +\\infty, \\frac{1}{(N+1)^2} \\rightarrow 0;\\\\ \\Rightarrow \\sum^{\\infty}_{n=1} \\frac{2n+1}{n^2(n+1)^2} = 1 - \\frac{1}{(\\infty+1)^2} = 1 - 0 = 1 \\end{align}$$;$$\\therefore$$ The series is convergent;$$\\therefore$$ The sum to infinity is 1.;;(iv) Using the answer from part (ii);$$\\begin{align} \\sum^{N}_{n=1} \\frac{2n+1}{n^2(n+1)^2} ;\\\\ = \\sum^{N-1}_{n=1} \\frac{2(n+1)+1}{(n+1)^2(n+1+1)^2} \\space (replace \\space n \\space with \\space n+1);\\\\ = \\sum^{N-1}_{n=1} \\frac{2n+1}{n^2(n+1)^2};\\\\ = 1-\\frac{1}{N^2}\\end{align}$$'),
('200704003003','(i);The function is defined by $$y = (1+x)^n ----(1)$$;$$\\therefore$$ To find its Maclaurin\'s series, (1) is differentiated successively wrt x:;$$\\begin{align} \\frac{dy}{dx} = n(1+x)^{n=1};\\\\ \\frac{d^{2}y}{dx^{2}} = n(n-1)(1+x)^{n-2};\\\\ \\frac{d^{3}y}{dx^{3}} = n(n-1)(n-2)(1+x)^{n-3}\\end{align}$$;;When x = 0,;$$\\begin{align} y = 1;\\\\ \\frac{dy}{dx} = n;\\\\ \\frac{d^{2}y}{dx^{2}} = n(n-1);\\\\ \\frac{d^{3}y}{dx^{3}} = n(n-1)(n-2)\\end{align}$$;;$$ \\therefore $$ The Maclaurin\'s series for (1+x)^n, up to and including x^3:;$$\\begin{align} y\\approx 1+ nx + \\frac{n(n-1)}{2!}x^2+\\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)}{3!}x^3 \\end{align}$$;;(ii);$$ \\therefore $$ Expansion of $$ (4-x)^{\\frac{3}{2}(1+2x^2)^{\\frac{3}{2}} }$$ up to and including $$x^3$$;$$\\begin{align} = 4^{\\frac{3}{2}}\\left(1-\\frac{x}{4}\\right)^{\\frac{3}{2}}(1+2x^2)^{\\frac{3}{2}};\\\\ \\approx 8\\left[1+\\left(\\frac{3}{2}\\left(-\\frac{x}{4}\\right)\\right)+\\frac{\\left(\\frac{3}{2}\\right)\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)}{2!}\\left(-\\frac{x}{4}\\right)^2+\\frac{\\left(\\frac{3}{2}\\right)\\left(\\frac{1}{2}\\right)\\left(-\\frac{1}{2}\\right)}{3!}\\left(-\\frac{x}{4}^3\\right)\\right]\\left[1+3x^2\\right];\\\\ = 3\\left(1-\\frac{3x}{8}+\\frac{3x^2}{128}+\\frac{x^3}{1024}\\right)\\left(1+3x^2\\right);\\\\ = \\left(8-3x+\\frac{3x^2}{16}+\\frac{x^3}{128}\\right)\\left(1+3x^2\\right);\\\\ \\approx 8 - 3x +\\left(\\frac{3}{16}+24\\right)x^2 + \\left(\\frac{1}{128}-9\\right)x^3;\\\\ = 8 - 3x + \\frac{387}{16}x^2-\\frac{1153}{128}x^3\\end{align}$$;;(iii);$$\\therefore$$ For expansion in part (ii) to be valid, $$\\left|\\frac{x}{4}\\right| < 1$$ and $$\\left|2x^2\\right| < 1$$.;$$\\begin{align} \\left|\\frac{x}{4}\\right| < 1 \\Rightarrow -4 < x <4;\\\\;\\\\ \\left|2x^2\\right| < 1 \\Rightarrow 2x^2 - 1 < 0;\\\\ x^2-\\frac{1}{2} < 0 \\Rightarrow \\left(x-\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}\\right)\\left(x+\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}\\right)<0;\\\\ \\Rightarrow -\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} < x < \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The set of values of $$x = \\left\\{x \\in \\mathbb{R}: -\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2} < x < \\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}\\right\\}$$'),
('200704003004','(i) ;$$\\therefore$$ The exact value of $$\\int^{\\frac{2}{3}\\pi}_{0} \\sin^{2}{x} \\space dx$$;$$\\begin{align} = \\int^{\\frac{2}{3}\\pi}_{0} \\frac{1-\\cos{2x}}{2} \\space dx \\space (Use \\space \\cos{2x} = 1-2\\sin^{2} x);\\\\ = \\left[\\frac{x}{2} - \\frac{\\sin{2x}}{4}\\right]^{\\frac{2}{3}\\pi}_{0};\\\\ = \\frac{5\\pi}{6} - \\frac{\\sin{\\frac{10\\pi}{3}}}{4};\\\\ = \\frac{5}{6}\\pi + \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{8}\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The exact value of $$\\int^{\\frac{5}{3}\\pi}_{0} \\cos^{2}{x} \\space dx$$;$$\\begin{align} = \\int^{\\frac{5}{3}\\pi}_{0} (1-\\sin^{2}{x}) \\space dx;\\\\ = \\left[x\\right]^{\\frac{5}{3}\\pi}_{0} - \\frac{5\\pi}{6} - \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{8};\\\\ = \\frac{5\\pi}{3} - \\frac{5\\pi}{6} - \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{8};\\\\ = \\frac{5}{6}\\pi - \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{8}\\end{align}$$;;(ii);The shaded region R is bounded by the curve $$y=x^2\\sin{x}$$, the line $$x=\\frac{1}{2}\\pi$$ and the part of the x-axis between 0  and $$\\frac{1}{2}\\pi$$ as shown.;img;;a);$$\\therefore$$ The exact area of R;$$\\begin{align} = \\int^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} x^2\\sin{x} \\space dx;\\\\ = \\left[(-\\cos{x})x^2\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} - \\int^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0}(-\\cos{x})(2x) \\space dx;\\\\ = 0 + \\left[(\\sin{x})(2x)\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} - \\int^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} 2\\sin{x}\\space dx;\\\\ = \\pi + \\left[2\\cos{x}\\right]^{\\frac{1}{2}\\pi}_{0} ;\\\\ = \\pi + (0-2) ;\\\\ = \\pi - 2 \\space units^2\\end{align}$$;;b) ;The bounded region R is made to rotate completely about the x-axis;$$\\therefore$$ The numerical value of volume of revolution;$$\\begin{align} = \\int^{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}_{0} \\pi y^2 \\space dx = \\int^{\\frac{\\pi}{2}}_{0} \\pi (x^4\\sin^{2}{x}) \\space dx;\\\\ = 5.391 \\space units^3 \\space (from \\space GC) (3dp)\\end{align}$$'),
('200704003005','(i);$$\\therefore$$ Real life example of a situation in which quota sampling could be used:;Quota sampling could be used by a market researcher to conduct a survey about how frequently shoppers at a particular mall visit the mall. A sample of 100 shoppers, subdivided according to age group or gender.;;Quota sampling is appropriate in this situation because it is quick and convenient to carry out, since the tasks of listing the whole population, randomly selecting the sample and following-up on non-respondents can be omitted from the process.;;Disadvantages of quota sampling:;Quota sampling is a non-random sampling method selection that is biased as those selected will be those who are most willing to cooperate.;The issue of the sample not representative of the general population leading to faulty conclusions remains a difficult problem;;(ii);$$\\therefore$$ Based on the situation described in part(i), stratified sampling cannot be used because the sampling frame is not accessible'),
('200704003006','Let X represent the number of people who have gene A out of a random sample of 10 $$\\Rightarrow$$ X ~ B(10,0.24);;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that our of 10, at most 4 have gene A;$$\\begin{align} = P(X \\leq 4);\\\\ = P(X=0) + P(X=1) + P(X=2) + P(X=3) + P(X=4);\\\\ = \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\0\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^0(0.76)^{10} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\1\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^1(0.76)^{9} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\2\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^2(0.76)^{8} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\3\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^3(0.76)^{7} + \\begin{pmatrix}10\\\\4\\end{pmatrix}(0.24)^4(0.76)^{6};\\\\ = 0.06428 + 0.20301 + 0.28849 + 0.24294 + 0.13425;\\\\ = 0.93297;\\\\ = 0.933 (3dp)(or \\space straight \\space from \\space GC)\\end{align}$$;;Another random sample of 1000 from the population is taken.;Using the appropriate approximations,;(i);Let Y represent the no. of people who have gene A out of a random sample of 1000 $$\\Rightarrow$$ Y ~ B(1000,0.24);Since n = 1000 is large, np = 240 > 5 and n(1-p) = 760 > 5, Y ~ N(240,182.4) approximately;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that between 230 and 260, inclusive have gene A;$$\\begin{align} = P(230 leq Y leq 260);\\\\ = P(229.5 leq Y \\leq 260.5) \\space (continuity \\space correction);\\\\ = P\\left(\\frac{229.5-240}{\\sqrt{182.4}} \\leq Z \\leq \\frac{260.5-240}{\\sqrt{182.4}}\\right);\\\\ = P(-0.7775 \\leq Z \\leq 1.15179);\\\\ = \\Phi(1.518)-[1-\\Phi(0.778)];\\\\ = 0.9355-[1-0.7817];\\\\ = 0.7172 = 0.717(3dp)\\end{align}$$;;(ii) ;Let u represent the number of people who have gene B out of a random sample of 1000 $$\\Rightarrow$$ U ~ B(1000,.003);Since n=1000 is large and np = 3<10, U ~ Po(3) approximately;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that at least 2 but fewer than 5 have gene B;$$\\begin{align} = P(2 \\leq U < 5);\\\\ = P(U=2) + P(U=3) + P(U=4);\\\\ = e^{-3}\\left[\\frac{(3)^2}{2!}+\\frac{(3)^3}{3!} + \\frac{(3)^4}{4!}\\right];\\\\ = 0.616(3dp)\\end{align}$$'),
('200704003007','Let X represent the time in hours taken by a student to complete a project, with population mean $$\\mu$$.;$$\\therefore$$ Unbiased estimate of mean, $$\\mu$$;$$\\begin{align} = \\overline{x} = \\frac{\\sum x}{n} = \\frac{4626}{150} = 30.84\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ Unbiased estimate of population variance, $$s^2$$;$$\\begin{align} =\\frac{1}{150-1}\\left[147691-\\frac{4626^2}{150}\\right];\\\\ = \\frac{5025.16}{149} = 33.7(3sf) \\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ To test if the population mean time for a student to complete the project exceeds 30 hours at 5% significance level,;Test $$H_0: \\mu = 30$$ against $$H_1:\\mu>30$$;One-tail test at 5% significance level, $$\\alpha = 0.05$$;Under $$H_0$$, since $$n=150$$ is large, by Central Limit Theorem, $$\\overline{X} ~ N(30, \\frac{33.7}{150})$$ approximately, where $$\\overline{X}$$ is the sample means.;Perform Z-test with: $$\\mu_0 = 30, s = \\sqrt{33.7259}, \\overline{x} = 30.84$$ and $$n=150$$.;From GC, p-value = 0.0382;Since p-value = 0.0382 < 0.05, we reject $$H_0$$ and conclude that there is sufficient evidence at the 5% significance level that the mean time for a student to complete the project exceeds 30hours.;;$$\\therefore$$ No assumption is needed in order for the test to be valid because since sample size is large, by Central Limit Theorem, the sample mean is approximately normally distributed.'),
('200704003008','(i) ;Let C and T represent mass of a randomly chosen chicken and turkey respectively, in kg $$\\Rightarrow \\space C \\sim N(2.2,0.5^2), T\\sim N(10.5,2.1^2)$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that a randomly chosen chicken costs more than $7;$$\\begin{align} = P(3C > 7);\\\\ = P\\left(C > \\frac{7}{3}\\right) ;\\\\ = P\\left(Z > \\frac{\\frac{7}{3} - 2.2}{0.5}\\right) ;\\\\ = P(Z > 0.2667);\\\\ = 1- \\Phi(0.267);\\\\ = 0.3947 = 0.395(3dp)\\end{align}$$;;(ii) ;The probability that a randomly chosen turkey costs more than $55 ;$$\\begin{align} = P(5T > 55);\\\\ = P\\left(T > \\frac{55}{5}\\right) ;\\\\ = P\\left(Z > \\frac{11-10.5}{2.1}\\right);\\\\ = P(Z > 0.2381);\\\\ = 1-\\Phi(0.238);\\\\ = 0.4059\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ Probability that both a random chicken costs more than $7 and random turkey costs more than $55;$$\\begin{align} =  P(C > \\frac{7}{3}) \\times P(T > 11);\\\\ = 0.347 \\times 0.4059;\\\\ = 0.1602 = 0.160 (2dp)\\end{align}$$;;(iii);Let Y be the cost of 3 chickens and 5 turkeys;Y = 3C + 5T;Y~N$$\\left(3(2.2) + 5(10.5), 3^2(0.5^2)+5^2(2.1^2) \\right)$$;$$\\Rightarrow$$ Y~N(59.1,112.5);;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that the total selling price of a randomly chosen chicken and a randomly chosen turkey is more than $62;$$\\begin{align} = P(Y > 62);\\\\ = P\\left(Z > \\frac{62-59.1}{\\sqrt{112.5}}\\right) ;\\\\ = P(Z > 0.2734);\\\\ = 1 - \\Phi(0.273);\\\\ = 0.3924 = 0.392(2dp)\\end{align}$$;;(iv) ;The reason why the answer to part (iii) is greater than the answer to part(ii) is because the condition for the total selling price of chicken and turkey exceeds $62[part(iii)] is less restrictive than the condition for the selling price of chicken is greater than $7 and at the same time, the selling price of turkey is greater than $55[part(ii)]'),
('200704003009','(i);a) The number of different possible arrangement = 12! = 479001600;b) The number of different possible orders in which each man stands next to his wife  = 6! x $$(2^6)$$ = 46080;(6 couples bundled together can be arranged in 6! ways and within each couple, husband and wife can switch positions.);;(ii);a) The number of different possible arrangements = (12-1)! = 11! - 39916800;b) The number of different possible arrangement if men and women alternate = 5! x 6! = 86400;(6 women first arranged in 5! ways, then men arrange in between them in 6! ways.);c) The number of different possible arrangements if each man stand next to his wife and men and women alternate = (6-1)!x2! = 240;(6 couples arranged in 5! ways; all wives sit to the right of the husband or the other way round'),
('200704003010','The probability tree showing the above information:;img;;Let S denote a successful shot(Hit) and F denote a unsuccessful shot(Miss);(i);The probability that all 3 shots were successful  $$\\begin{align}= P(SSS) = \\frac{1}{8} \\times \\frac{2}{8} \\times \\frac{4}{8} = \\frac{1}{64} \\end{align}$$;;(ii);The probability that at least 2 shots were successful;$$\\begin{align} = P(SSS) + F(FSS) + P(SFS) + P(SSF);\\\\ = \\frac{1}{64} + \\left(\\frac{7}{8} \\times \\frac{1}{8} \\times \\frac{2}{8}\\right) + \\left(\\frac{1}{8} \\times \\frac{6}{8} \\times \\frac{2}{8}\\right) + \\left(\\frac{1}{8} \\times \\frac{2}{8} \\times \\frac{4}{8}\\right);\\\\ = \\frac{1}{64} + \\frac{14}{512} + \\frac{12}{512} + \\frac{8}{512};\\\\ = \\frac{21}{256}\\end{align}$$;;(iii);The probability that the $$3^{rd}$$ shot is successful given exactly 2 of the three shots are successful;$$\\begin{align} = \\frac{P(FSS) +P(SFS)}{P(FSS)+P(SFS)+P(SSF)};\\\\ = \\frac{\\frac{14}{512}+\\frac{12}{512}}{\\frac{14}{512}+\\frac{12}{512}+\\frac{8}{512}} ;\\\\ = \\frac{26}{34} = \\frac{13}{17}\\end{align}$$'),
('200704003011','$$\\therefore$$ To find equation of regression line of x on t:;Let n be the sample size = 9;$$ \\sum x = 82+65+43+37+22+19+12+6+2 = 288 $$;$$ \\sum x^2 = 82^2+65^2+43^2+37^2+22^2+19^2+12^2+6^2+2^2 = 15196 $$;$$ \\sum t = 15+30+60+90+120+150+180+240+300=1185$$;$$ \\sum t^2 = 15^2+30^2+60^2+90^2+120^2+150^2+180^2+240^2+300^2=229725$$;$$ \\sum xt = (82)(15)+(65)(30)+(43)(60)+(37)(90)+(22)(120)+(19)(150)+(12)(180)+(6)(240)+(2)(300) = 18780 $$;;$$\\begin{align} \\overline{x} = \\frac{\\sum x}{n} = \\frac{288}{9} = 32;\\\\ \\overline{t} = \\frac{\\sum t}{n} = \\frac{1185}{9} = 131.67\\end{align}$$;;Regression coefficient of x and t:;$$\\begin{align} \\beta_x = \\frac{\\sum xt - \\frac{\\sum x \\sum t}{n}}{\\sum t^2 - \\frac{(\\sum t)^2}{n}} ;\\\\ = \\frac{18780-\\frac{288 x 1185}{9}}{229725 - \\frac{1185^2}{9}};\\\\ = -0.2597\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ Equation of the regression line of x on t:;$$\\begin{align} x - \\overline{x} = \\beta_x(t-\\overline{t});\\\\ \\Rightarrow x - 32 = -0.2597(t-131.67);\\\\ \\Rightarrow x = -0.2597t + 66.19;\\\\ \\Rightarrow x = -0.260t + 66.2 (from \\space GC) \\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The corresponding estimated value of x when t = 300;$$ x_{300} = 66.1940-0.259701(300) = -11.72 = -11.7(3sf) $$;;$$\\therefore$$ Comment on the suitability of the model:;This estimated value of x is impossible because the concentration of the drug in the bloodstream cannot be negative. Besides, the curved nature of the graph suggests that a straight line is not a good model.;;The variable y is defined by y = ln x;(i);For the variables y and t, ;$$\\therefore$$ Let n be the sample size = 9;$$ \\sum y = \\ln 82 + \\ln 65 + \\ln 43 + \\ln 37 + \\ln 22 + \\ln 19 + \\ln 12 + \\ln 6 + \\ln 2 = ;26.959 $$;$$ \\sum y^2 = (\\ln 82)^2 + (\\ln 65)^2 + (\\ln 43)^2 + (\\ln 37)^2 + (\\ln 22)^2 + (\\ln 19)^2 + (\\ln 12)^2 + (\\ln 6)^2 + (\\ln 2)^2 = 92.120 $$;$$ \\sum t = 15+30+60+90+120+150+180+240+300=1185$$;$$ \\sum yt = (\\ln 82)(15) + (\\ln 65)(30) + (\\ln 43)(60) + (\\ln 37)(90) + (\\ln 22)(120) + (\\ln 19)(150) + (\\ln 12)(180) + (\\ln 6)(240) + (\\ln 2)(300) = 2639.8 $$;;$$\\therefore$$ The product moment correlation coefficient;$$\\begin{align} r = \\frac{\\sum yt - \\frac{\\sum y \\sum t}{n}}{\\sqrt{\\left(\\sum t^2 - \\frac{\\left(\\sum t\\right)^2}{n}\\right)\\left(\\sum y^2 - \\frac{\\left(\\sum y\\right)^2}{n}\\right)}} \\\\ = \\frac{2639.8 - \\frac{26.959 \\times 1185}{9}}{\\sqrt{\\left(229725- \\frac{\\left(1185\\right)^2}{9}\\right)\\left(92.12 - \\frac{\\left(26.959\\right)^2}{9}\\right)}} ;\\\\ = -0.9941 = -0.994\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ Comment on the value:;The product moment correlation coefficient of the linear model;$$\\begin{align} r =  \\frac{\\sum xt - \\frac{\\sum x \\sum t}{n}}{\\sqrt{\\left(\\sum t^2 - \\frac{\\left(\\sum t\\right)^2}{n}\\right)\\left(\\sum x^2 - \\frac{\\left(\\sum x\\right)^2}{n}\\right)}} \\\\ = \\frac{18780 - \\frac{288 \\times 1185}{9}}{\\sqrt{\\left(229725- \\frac{\\left(1185\\right)^2}{9}\\right)\\left(15196 - \\frac{\\left(288\\right)^2}{9}\\right)}} ;\\\\ = -0.9117 = -0.912\\end{align}$$;;This indicates a stronger correlation is between y and t (|r| = 0.994) and this |value| is closer to 1 than the value obtained from the linear model (|r| = 0.912).;;(ii) $$\\therefore$$ Regression coefficient of y and t:;$$\\begin{align} \\beta_y =  \\frac{\\sum yt - \\frac{\\sum y \\sum t}{n}}{\\sum t^2 - \\frac{\\left(\\sum t\\right)^2}{n}} ;\\\\ = \\frac{2639.8 - \\frac{26.959 \\times 1185}{9}}{229725- \\frac{\\left(1185\\right)^2}{9}};\\\\ = -0.01234;\\\\ \\overline{y} = \\frac{\\sum y}{n} = \\frac{26.959}{9} = 2.995\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ Equation of regression line of y on t:;$$\\begin{align} y - \\overline{y} = \\beta_y(t-\\overline{t});\\\\ \\Rightarrow y - 2.995 = -0.01234(t-131.67);\\\\ \\Rightarrow y = -0.01234t + 4.621;\\\\ \\Rightarrow y = -0.0123t + 4.62 \\space (from \\space GC) \\end{align}$$;;When the drug concentration (x) is 15 micrograms per litre,;$$\\begin{align}\\Rightarrow y = \\ln 15;\\\\ \\Rightarrow \\ln 15 = 4.62 - 0.0123t;\\\\ t = 155.02 \\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The best estimate of time when drug concentration is 15 mg $$\\ell^{-1}$$: t = 155min');
